# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: photonics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Many different physical mechanisms can cause nonlinearities in the optical behaviour of a material, i.e. the motion of bound electrons, field-induced vibrational or orientational motions, optically-induced acoustic waves and thermal effects.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] The motion of bound electrons, in particular, has a very short response timescale, so it is of particular relevance in the context of ultrafast nonlinear optics.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] The simplest way to picture this behaviour in a semiclassical way is to use a phenomenological model: an anharmonic oscillator can model the forced oscillations of a bound electron inside the medium.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Maxwell's equations are linear in vacuum, so, nonlinear processes only occur in media.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] However, the theory of quantum electrodynamics (QED) predicts that, above the Schwinger limit, vacuum itself can behave in a nonlinear way.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] The description of nonlinear optics usually presented in textbooks is the perturbative regime, which is valid when the input intensity remains below 1014 W/cm2, which implies that the electric field is well below the intensity of interatomic fields.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] This approach allows to use a Taylor series to write down the polarization density as a polynomial sum.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] However, some nonlinear effects were discovered before the development of the laser.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] The theoretical basis for many nonlinear processes was first described in Bloembergen's monograph "Nonlinear Optics".
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Nonlinear optics explains nonlinear response of properties such as frequency, polarization, phase or path of incident light.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Nonlinear effects fall into two qualitatively different categories, parametric and non-parametric effects.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] A parametric non-linearity is an interaction in which the quantum state of the nonlinear material is not changed by the interaction with the optical field.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] As a consequence of this, the process is "instantaneous".
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Energy and momentum are conserved in the optical field, making phase matching important and polarization-dependent.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] where the coefficients χ(*n*) are the *n*-th-order susceptibilities of the medium, and the presence of such a term is generally referred to as an *n*-th-order nonlinearity.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Note that the polarization density **P**(*t*) and electrical field **E**(*t*) are considered as scalar quantities for simplicity.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Central to the study of electromagnetic waves is the wave equation.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] where **P**NL is the nonlinear part of the polarization density, and *n* is the refractive index, which comes from the linear term in **P**.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] is true in general, even for an isotropic medium.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] The nonlinear wave equation is an inhomogeneous differential equation.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] The general solution comes from the study of partial differential equations and can be obtained by the use of a Green's function.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] acts as a driver/source of the electromagnetic waves.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] One of the consequences of this is a nonlinear interaction that results in energy being mixed or coupled between different frequencies, which is often called a "wave mixing".
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] In general, an *n*-th order nonlinearity will lead to (*n* + 1)-wave mixing.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] where "c.c." stands for complex conjugate.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] These three-wave mixing processes correspond to the nonlinear effects known as second-harmonic generation, sum-frequency generation, difference-frequency generation and optical rectification respectively.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Note: Parametric generation and amplification is a variation of difference-frequency generation, where the lower frequency of one of the two generating fields is much weaker (parametric amplification) or completely absent (parametric generation).
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] In the latter case, the fundamental quantum-mechanical uncertainty in the electric field initiates the process.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] The above ignores the position dependence of the electrical fields.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] at position $\mathbf {x}$ , with the wave vector $\|\mathbf {k} _{j}\|=\mathbf {n} (\omega _{j})\omega _{j}/c$ , where c is the velocity of light in vacuum, and $\mathbf {n} (\omega _{j})$ is the index of refraction of the medium at angular frequency $\omega _{j}$ .
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] At each position $\mathbf {x}$ within the nonlinear medium, the oscillating second-order polarization radiates at angular frequency $\omega _{3}$ and a corresponding wave vector $\|\mathbf {k} _{3}\|=\mathbf {n} (\omega _{3})\omega _{3}/c$ .
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] The above equation is known as the *phase-matching condition*.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Typically, three-wave mixing is done in a birefringent crystalline material, where the refractive index depends on the polarization and direction of the light that passes through.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] The polarizations of the fields and the orientation of the crystal are chosen such that the phase-matching condition is fulfilled.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] This phase-matching technique is called angle tuning.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Typically a crystal has three axes, one or two of which have a different refractive index than the other one(s).
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Uniaxial crystals, for example, have a single preferred axis, called the extraordinary (e) axis, while the other two are ordinary axes (o) (see crystal optics).
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] There are several schemes of choosing the polarizations for this crystal type.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] If the signal and idler have the same polarization, it is called "type-I phase matching", and if their polarizations are perpendicular, it is called "type-II phase matching".
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] However, other conventions exist that specify further which frequency has what polarization relative to the crystal axis.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] These types are listed below, with the convention that the signal wavelength is shorter than the idler wavelength.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Most common nonlinear crystals are negative uniaxial, which means that the *e* axis has a smaller refractive index than the *o* axes.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] In those crystals, type-I and -II phase matching are usually the most suitable schemes.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] In positive uniaxial crystals, types VII and VIII are more suitable.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Types II and III are essentially equivalent, except that the names of signal and idler are swapped when the signal has a longer wavelength than the idler.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] For this reason, they are sometimes called IIA and IIB.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] The type numbers V–VIII are less common than I and II and variants.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] One undesirable effect of angle tuning is that the optical frequencies involved do not propagate collinearly with each other.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] This is due to the fact that the extraordinary wave propagating through a birefringent crystal possesses a Poynting vector that is not parallel to the propagation vector.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] This would lead to beam walk-off, which limits the nonlinear optical conversion efficiency.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Two other methods of phase matching avoid beam walk-off by forcing all frequencies to propagate at a 90° with respect to the optical axis of the crystal.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] These methods are called temperature tuning and quasi-phase-matching.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Temperature tuning is used when the pump (laser) frequency polarization is orthogonal to the signal and idler frequency polarization.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] The birefringence in some crystals, in particular lithium niobate is highly temperature-dependent.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] The crystal temperature is controlled to achieve phase-matching conditions.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] The other method is quasi-phase-matching.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] In this method the frequencies involved are not constantly locked in phase with each other, instead the crystal axis is flipped at a regular interval Λ, typically 15 micrometres in length.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Hence, these crystals are called periodically poled.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] This results in the polarization response of the crystal to be shifted back in phase with the pump beam by reversing the nonlinear susceptibility.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] This allows net positive energy flow from the pump into the signal and idler frequencies.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] In this case, the crystal itself provides the additional wavevector *k* = 2π/Λ (and hence momentum) to satisfy the phase-matching condition.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Quasi-phase-matching can be expanded to chirped gratings to get more bandwidth and to shape an SHG pulse like it is done in a dazzler.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] SHG of a pump and self-phase modulation (emulated by second-order processes) of the signal and an optical parametric amplifier can be integrated monolithically.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] The above holds for $\chi ^{(2)}$ processes.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] It can be extended for processes where $\chi ^{(3)}$ is nonzero, something that is generally true in any medium without any symmetry restrictions; in particular resonantly enhanced sum or difference frequency mixing in gasses is frequently used for extreme or "vacuum" ultra-violet light generation.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] In common scenarios, such as mixing in dilute gases, the non-linearity is weak and so the light beams are focused which, unlike the plane wave approximation used above, introduces a pi phase shift on each light beam, complicating the phase-matching requirements.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Conveniently, difference frequency mixing with $\chi ^{(3)}$ cancels this focal phase shift and often has a nearly self-canceling overall phase-matching condition, which relatively simplifies broad wavelength tuning compared to sum frequency generation.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] In $\chi ^{(3)}$ all four frequencies are mixing simultaneously, as opposed to sequential mixing via two $\chi ^{(2)}$ processes.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] The Kerr effect can be described as a $\chi ^{(3)}$ as well.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] At high peak powers the Kerr effect can cause filamentation of light in air, in which the light travels without dispersion or divergence in a self-generated waveguide.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] At even high intensities the Taylor series, which led the domination of the lower orders, does not converge anymore and instead a time based model is used.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] When a noble gas atom is hit by an intense laser pulse, which has an electric field strength comparable to the Coulomb field of the atom, the outermost electron may be ionized from the atom.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Once freed, the electron can be accelerated by the electric field of the light, first moving away from the ion, then back toward it as the field changes direction.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] The electron may then recombine with the ion, releasing its energy in the form of a photon.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] The light is emitted at every peak of the laser light field which is intense enough, producing a series of attosecond light flashes.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] The photon energies generated by this process can extend past the 800th harmonic order up to a few KeV.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] This is called high-order harmonic generation.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] The laser must be linearly polarized, so that the electron returns to the vicinity of the parent ion.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] High-order harmonic generation has been observed in noble gas jets, cells, and gas-filled capillary waveguides.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] One of the most commonly used frequency-mixing processes is **frequency doubling**, or second-harmonic generation.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] With this technique, the 1064 nm output from Nd:YAG lasers or the 800 nm output from Ti:sapphire lasers can be converted to visible light, with wavelengths of 532 nm (green) or 400 nm (violet) respectively.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Practically, frequency doubling is carried out by placing a nonlinear medium in a laser beam.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] While there are many types of nonlinear media, the most common media are crystals.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Commonly used crystals are BBO (β-barium borate), KDP (potassium dihydrogen phosphate), KTP (potassium titanyl phosphate), and lithium niobate.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] It is possible, using nonlinear optical processes, to exactly reverse the propagation direction and phase variation of a beam of light.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] The reversed beam is called a *conjugate* beam, and thus the technique is known as **optical phase conjugation** (also called *time reversal*, *wavefront reversal* and is significantly different from *retroreflection*).
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] A device producing the phase-conjugation effect is known as a **phase-conjugate mirror** (PCM).
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] One can interpret optical phase conjugation as being analogous to a real-time holographic process.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] In this case, the interacting beams simultaneously interact in a nonlinear optical material to form a dynamic hologram (two of the three input beams), or real-time diffraction pattern, in the material.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] The third incident beam diffracts at this dynamic hologram, and, in the process, reads out the *phase-conjugate* wave.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] In effect, all three incident beams interact (essentially) simultaneously to form several real-time holograms, resulting in a set of diffracted output waves that phase up as the "time-reversed" beam.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] In the language of nonlinear optics, the interacting beams result in a nonlinear polarization within the material, which coherently radiates to form the phase-conjugate wave.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Reversal of wavefront means a perfect reversal of photons' linear momentum and angular momentum.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] The reversal of angular momentum means reversal of both polarization state and orbital angular momentum.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Reversal of orbital angular momentum of optical vortex is due to the perfect match of helical phase profiles of the incident and reflected beams.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Optical phase conjugation is implemented via stimulated Brillouin scattering, four-wave mixing, three-wave mixing, static linear holograms and some other tools.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] The most common way of producing optical phase conjugation is to use a four-wave mixing technique, though it is also possible to use processes such as stimulated Brillouin scattering.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] where *Ej* are the electric field amplitudes. Ξ1 and Ξ2 are known as the two pump waves, with Ξ3 being the signal wave, and Ξ4 being the generated conjugate wave.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] resulting in generation of waves with frequencies given by ω = ±ω1 ± ω2 ± ω3 in addition to third-harmonic generation waves with ω = 3ω1, 3ω2, 3ω3.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] As above, the phase-matching condition determines which of these waves is the dominant.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] This is the generating field for the phase-conjugate beam, Ξ4.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Its direction is given by **k**4 = **k**1 + **k**2 − **k**3, and so if the two pump beams are counterpropagating (**k**1 = −**k**2), then the conjugate and signal beams propagate in opposite directions (**k**4 = −**k**3).
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] This results in the retroreflecting property of the effect.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] that is, the generated beam amplitude is the complex conjugate of the signal beam amplitude.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Since the imaginary part of the amplitude contains the phase of the beam, this results in the reversal of phase property of the effect.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Note that the constant of proportionality between the signal and conjugate beams can be greater than 1.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] This is effectively a mirror with a reflection coefficient greater than 100%, producing an amplified reflection.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] The power for this comes from the two pump beams, which are depleted by the process.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] The frequency of the conjugate wave can be different from that of the signal wave.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] If the pump waves are of frequency ω1 = ω2 = ω, and the signal wave is higher in frequency such that ω3 = ω + Δω, then the conjugate wave is of frequency ω4 = ω − Δω.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] which is a linear momentum density of electromagnetic field.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] The above identities are valid *locally*, i.e. in each space point $\mathbf {r}$ in a given moment t for an *ideal phase-conjugating mirror*.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] The angular momentum projection on propagation axis has *discrete values* $\pm \hbar \ell$ .
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] In *quantum electrodynamics* the interpretation of phase conjugation is much simpler compared to *classical electrodynamics*.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Optical fields transmitted through nonlinear Kerr media can also display pattern formation owing to the nonlinear medium amplifying spatial and temporal noise.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] The effect is referred to as optical modulation instability.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] This has been observed both in photo-refractive, photonic lattices, as well as photo-reactive systems.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] In the latter case, optical nonlinearity is afforded by reaction-induced increases in refractive index.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Examples of pattern formation are spatial solitons and vortex lattices in framework of nonlinear Schrödinger equation.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] The early studies of nonlinear optics and materials focused on the inorganic solids.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] With the development of nonlinear optics, molecular optical properties were investigated, forming molecular nonlinear optics.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] The traditional approaches used in the past to enhance nonlinearities include extending chromophore π-systems, adjusting bond length alternation, inducing intramolecular charge transfer, extending conjugation in 2D, and engineering multipolar charge distributions.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Recently, many novel directions were proposed for enhanced nonlinearity and light manipulation, including twisted chromophores, combining rich density of states with bond alternation, microscopic cascading of second-order nonlinearity, etc.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Due to the distinguished advantages, molecular nonlinear optics have been widely used in the biophotonics field, including bioimaging, phototherapy, biosensing, etc.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Molecular nonlinear optics relate optical properties of bulk matter to their microscopic molecular properties.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Certain molecular materials have the ability to be optimized for their optical nonlinearity at the microscopic and bulk levels.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Due to the delocalization of electrons in π bonds electrons are more easily responsive to applied optical fields and tend to produce larger linear and nonlinear optical responses than those in single (𝜎) bonds.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] In these systems linear response scales with the length of the conjugated pi system, while nonlinear response scales even more rapidly.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] One of the many applications of molecular nonlinear optics is the use in nonlinear bioimaging.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] These nonlinear materials, like multi-photon chromophores, are used as biomarkers for two-photon spectroscopy, in which the attenuation of incident light intensity as it passes through the sample is written as ${-dI \over dx}={N\delta I^{2} \over \hbar \omega }$ .
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] where N is the number of particles per unit volume, I is intensity of light, and δ is the two photon absorption cross section.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] The resulting signal adopts a Lorentzian lineshape with a cross-section proportional to the difference in dipole moments of ground and final states.
[src:photonics/nonlinear-optics] Similar highly conjugated chromophores with strong donor-acceptor characteristics are used due to their large difference in the dipole moments, and current efforts in extending their pi-conjugated systems to enhance their nonlinear optical properties are being made.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] An **optical amplifier** is a device that amplifies an optical signal directly, without the need to first convert it to an electrical signal.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] An optical amplifier may be thought of as a laser without an optical cavity, or one in which feedback from the cavity is suppressed.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Optical amplifiers are important in optical communication and laser physics.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] They are used as optical repeaters in the long distance fiber-optic cables which carry much of the world's telecommunication links.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] There are several different physical mechanisms that can be used to amplify a light signal, which correspond to the major types of optical amplifiers.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] In doped fiber amplifiers and bulk lasers, stimulated emission in the amplifier's gain medium causes amplification of incoming light.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] In semiconductor optical amplifiers (SOAs), electron–hole recombination occurs.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] In Raman amplifiers, Raman scattering of incoming light with phonons in the lattice of the gain medium produces photons coherent with the incoming photons.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Parametric amplifiers use parametric amplification.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The principle of optical amplification was invented by Gordon Gould on November 13, 1957.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] He filed US Patent US80453959A on April 6, 1959, titled "Light Amplifiers Employing Collisions to Produce Population Inversions" (subsequently amended as a continuation in part and finally issued as U.S. patent 4,746,201A on May 4, 1988).
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The patent covered “the amplification of light by the stimulated emission of photons from ions, atoms or molecules in gaseous, liquid or solid state.” In total, Gould obtained 48 patents related to the optical amplifier that covered 80% of the lasers on the market at the time of issuance.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Gould co-founded an optical telecommunications equipment firm, Optelecom Inc., that helped start Ciena Corp with his former head of Light Optics Research, David Huber and Kevin Kimberlin.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Huber and Steve Alexander of Ciena invented the dual-stage optical amplifier (U.S. patent 5,159,601) that was a key to the first dense wave division multiplexing (DWDM) system, that they released in June 1996.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] This marked the start of optical networking.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Optical amplification WDM systems are the common basis of all local, metro, national, intercontinental and subsea telecommunications networks and the technology of choice for the fiber optic backbones of the Internet (e.g. fiber-optic cables form a basis of modern-day computer networking).
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Almost any laser active gain medium can be pumped to produce gain for light at the wavelength of a laser made with the same material as its gain medium.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Such amplifiers are commonly used to produce high power laser systems.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Special types such as regenerative amplifiers and chirped-pulse amplifiers are used to amplify ultrashort pulses.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Amplification is achieved by stimulated emission of photons from dopant ions in the doped fiber.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The pump laser excites ions into a higher energy from where they can decay via stimulated emission of a photon at the signal wavelength back to a lower energy level.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The excited ions can also decay spontaneously (spontaneous emission) or even through nonradiative processes involving interactions with phonons of the glass matrix.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] These last two decay mechanisms compete with stimulated emission reducing the efficiency of light amplification.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The *amplification window* of an optical amplifier is the range of optical wavelengths for which the amplifier yields a usable gain.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The amplification window is determined by the spectroscopic properties of the dopant ions, the glass structure of the optical fiber, and the wavelength and power of the pump laser.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Although the electronic transitions of an isolated ion are very well defined, broadening of the energy levels occurs when the ions are incorporated into the glass of the optical fiber and thus the amplification window is also broadened.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] This broadening is both homogeneous (all ions exhibit the same broadened spectrum) and inhomogeneous (different ions in different glass locations exhibit different spectra).
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Homogeneous broadening arises from the interactions with phonons of the glass, while inhomogeneous broadening is caused by differences in the glass sites where different ions are hosted.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Different sites expose ions to different local electric fields, which shifts the energy levels via the Stark effect.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] In addition, the Stark effect also removes the degeneracy of energy states having the same total angular momentum (specified by the quantum number J).
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Thus, for example, the trivalent erbium ion (Er3+) has a ground state with J = 15/2, and in the presence of an electric field splits into J + 1/2 = 8 sublevels with slightly different energies.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The first excited state has J = 13/2 and therefore a Stark manifold with 7 sublevels.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Transitions from the J = 13/2 excited state to the J= 15/2 ground state are responsible for the gain at 1500 nm wavelength.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The gain spectrum of the EDFA has several peaks that are smeared by the above broadening mechanisms.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The net result is a very broad spectrum (30 nm in silica, typically).
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The broad gain-bandwidth of fiber amplifiers make them particularly useful in wavelength-division multiplexed communications systems as a single amplifier can be utilized to amplify all signals being carried on a fiber and whose wavelengths fall within the gain window.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] An *erbium-doped waveguide amplifier* (EDWA) is an optical amplifier that uses a waveguide to boost an optical signal.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] A relatively high-powered beam of light known as the pump light is mixed with the amplified input signal using a coupler.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The input signal and the pump light must be at significantly different wavelengths.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The mixed light is guided into a section of fiber with erbium ions included in the core.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] This high-powered light beam excites the erbium ions to their higher-energy state.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] When the photons belonging to the signal at a different wavelength from the pump light meet the excited erbium ions, the erbium ions undergo stimulated emission and return to their lower-energy state.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] A significant point is that the erbium gives up its energy in the form of additional photons which are exactly in the same phase, frequency, and direction as the signal being amplified.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] So the signal is amplified along its direction of travel only.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] This is not unusual – when an atom "lases" it always gives up its energy in the same direction and phase as the incoming light.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Thus all of the additional signal power is guided in the same fiber mode as the incoming signal.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The pump light can be sent into the fiber in the same direction (forward pumping) or opposite direction of the signal (backwards pumping).
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] An optical isolator is usually placed at the output to prevent reflections returning from the attached fiber.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Such reflections disrupt amplifier operation and in the extreme case can cause the amplifier to become a laser.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The erbium doped amplifier is a high gain amplifier.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The principal source of noise in DFAs is amplified spontaneous emission (ASE), which has a spectrum approximately the same as the gain spectrum of the amplifier.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Noise figure in an ideal DFA is 3 dB, while practical amplifiers can have noise figure as large as 6–8 dB.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] As well as decaying via stimulated emission, electrons in the upper energy level can also decay by spontaneous emission, which occurs at random, depending upon the glass structure and inversion level.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Photons are emitted spontaneously in all directions, but a proportion of those will be emitted in a direction that falls within the numerical aperture of the fiber and are thus captured and guided by the fiber.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Those photons captured may then interact with other dopant ions, and are thus amplified by stimulated emission.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The initial spontaneous emission is therefore amplified in the same manner as the signals, hence the term a*mplified spontaneous emission*.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] ASE is emitted by the amplifier in both the forward and reverse directions, but only the forward ASE is a direct concern to system performance since that noise will co-propagate with the signal to the receiver where it degrades system performance.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Counter-propagating ASE can, however, lead to degradation of the amplifier's performance since the ASE can deplete the inversion level and thereby reduce the gain of the amplifier and increase the noise produced relative to the desired signal gain.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Noise figure can be analyzed in both the optical domain and in the electrical domain.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] In the optical domain, measurement of the ASE, the optical signal gain, and signal wavelength using an optical spectrum analyzer permits calculation of the noise figure.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] For the electrical measurement method, the detected photocurrent noise is evaluated with a low-noise electrical spectrum analyzer, which along with measurement of the amplifier gain permits a noise figure measurement.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Generally, the optical technique provides a more simple method, though it is not inclusive of excess noise effects captured by the electrical method such multi-path interference (MPI) noise generation.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] In both methods, attention to effects such as the spontaneous emission accompanying the input signal are critical to accurate measurement of noise figure.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Gain is achieved in a DFA due to population inversion of the dopant ions.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The inversion level of a DFA is set, primarily, by the power of the pump wavelength and the power at the amplified wavelengths.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] As the signal power increases, or the pump power decreases, the inversion level will reduce and thereby the gain of the amplifier will be reduced.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] This effect is known as gain saturation – as the signal level increases, the amplifier saturates and cannot produce any more output power, and therefore the gain reduces.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Saturation is also commonly known as gain compression.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] To achieve optimum noise performance DFAs are operated under a significant amount of gain compression (10 dB typically), since that reduces the rate of spontaneous emission, thereby reducing ASE.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Another advantage of operating the DFA in the gain saturation region is that small fluctuations in the input signal power are reduced in the output amplified signal: smaller input signal powers experience larger (less saturated) gain, while larger input powers see less gain.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The leading edge of the pulse is amplified, until the saturation energy of the gain medium is reached.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] In some condition, the width (FWHM) of the pulse is reduced.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Due to the inhomogeneous portion of the linewidth broadening of the dopant ions, the gain spectrum has an inhomogeneous component and gain saturation occurs, to a small extent, in an inhomogeneous manner.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] This effect is known as *spectral hole burning* because a high power signal at one wavelength can 'burn' a hole in the gain for wavelengths close to that signal by saturation of the inhomogeneously broadened ions.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Spectral holes vary in width depending on the characteristics of the optical fiber in question and the power of the burning signal, but are typically less than 1 nm at the short wavelength end of the C-band, and a few nm at the long wavelength end of the C-band.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The depth of the holes are very small, though, making it difficult to observe in practice.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Although the DFA is essentially a polarization independent amplifier, a small proportion of the dopant ions interact preferentially with certain polarizations and a small dependence on the polarization of the input signal may occur (typically < 0.5 dB).
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] This is called polarization dependent gain (PDG).
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The absorption and emission cross sections of the ions can be modeled as ellipsoids with the major axes aligned at random in all directions in different glass sites.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The random distribution of the orientation of the ellipsoids in a glass produces a macroscopically isotropic medium, but a strong pump laser induces an anisotropic distribution by selectively exciting those ions that are more aligned with the optical field vector of the pump.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Also, those excited ions aligned with the signal field produce more stimulated emission.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The change in gain is thus dependent on the alignment of the polarizations of the pump and signal lasers – i.e. whether the two lasers are interacting with the same sub-set of dopant ions or not.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] In an ideal doped fiber without birefringence, the PDG would be inconveniently large.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Fortunately, in optical fibers small amounts of birefringence are always present and, furthermore, the fast and slow axes vary randomly along the fiber length.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] A typical DFA has several tens of meters, long enough to already show this randomness of the birefringence axes.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] These two combined effects (which in transmission fibers give rise to polarization mode dispersion) produce a misalignment of the relative polarizations of the signal and pump lasers along the fiber, thus tending to average out the PDG.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The result is that PDG is very difficult to observe in a single amplifier (but is noticeable in links with several cascaded amplifiers).
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The erbium-doped fiber amplifier (EDFA) is the most deployed fiber amplifier as its amplification window coincides with the third transmission window of silica-based optical fiber.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The core of a silica fiber is doped with trivalent erbium ions (Er3+) and can be efficiently pumped with a laser at or near wavelengths of 980 nm and 1480 nm, and gain is exhibited in the 1550 nm region.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The EDFA amplification region varies from application to application and can be anywhere from a few nm up to ~80 nm.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Typical use of EDFA in telecommunications calls for *Conventional*, or C-band amplifiers (from ~1525 nm to ~1565 nm) or *Long*, or L-band amplifiers (from ~1565 nm to ~1610 nm).
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Both of these bands can be amplified by EDFAs, but it is normal to use two different amplifiers, each optimized for one of the bands.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The principal difference between C- and L-band amplifiers is that a longer length of doped fiber is used in L-band amplifiers.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The longer length of fiber allows a lower inversion level to be used, thereby giving emission at longer wavelengths (due to the band-structure of Erbium in silica) while still providing a useful amount of gain.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] EDFAs have two commonly used pumping bands – 980 nm and 1480 nm.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The 980 nm band has a higher absorption cross-section and is generally used where low-noise performance is required.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The absorption band is relatively narrow and so wavelength stabilised laser sources are typically needed.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The 1480 nm band has a lower, but broader, absorption cross-section and is generally used for higher power amplifiers.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] A combination of 980 nm and 1480 nm pumping is generally utilised in amplifiers.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Gain and lasing in erbium-doped fibers were first demonstrated in 1986–87 by two groups; one including David N.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Reekie, from the University of Southampton and one from AT&T Bell Laboratories, consisting of E.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The dual-stage optical amplifier which enabled dense wave division multiplexing (DWDM) was invented by Stephen B.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Thulium doped fiber amplifiers have been used in the S-band (1450–1490 nm) and Praseodymium doped amplifiers in the 1300 nm region.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] However, those regions have not seen any significant commercial use so far and so those amplifiers have not been the subject of as much development as the EDFA.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] However, Ytterbium doped fiber lasers and amplifiers, operating near 1 micrometre wavelength, have many applications in industrial processing of materials, as these devices can be made with extremely high output power (tens of kilowatts).
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Semiconductor optical amplifiers (SOAs) are amplifiers which use a semiconductor to provide the gain medium.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] These amplifiers have a similar structure to Fabry–Pérot laser diodes but with anti-reflection design elements at the end faces.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Recent designs include anti-reflective coatings and tilted wave guide and window regions which can reduce end face reflection to less than 0.001%.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Since this creates a loss of power from the cavity which is greater than the gain, it prevents the amplifier from acting as a laser.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Another type of SOA consists of two regions.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] One part has a structure of a Fabry-Pérot laser diode and the other has a tapered geometry in order to reduce the power density on the output facet.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Semiconductor optical amplifiers are typically made from group III-V compound semiconductors such as GaAs/AlGaAs, InP/InGaAs, InP/InGaAsP and InP/InAlGaAs, though any direct band gap semiconductors such as II-VI could conceivably be used.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Such amplifiers are often used in telecommunication systems in the form of fiber-pigtailed components, operating at signal wavelengths between 850 nm and 1600 nm and generating gains of up to 30 dB.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The semiconductor optical amplifier is of small size and electrically pumped.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] It can be potentially less expensive than the EDFA and can be integrated with semiconductor lasers, modulators, etc.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] However, the performance is still not comparable with the EDFA.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The SOA has higher noise, lower gain, moderate polarization dependence and high nonlinearity with fast transient time.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The main advantage of SOA is that all four types of nonlinear operations (cross gain modulation, cross phase modulation, wavelength conversion and four wave mixing) can be conducted.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Furthermore, SOA can be run with a low power laser.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] This originates from the short nanosecond or less upper state lifetime, so that the gain reacts rapidly to changes of pump or signal power and the changes of gain also cause phase changes which can distort the signals.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] This nonlinearity presents the most severe problem for optical communication applications.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] However it provides the possibility for gain in different wavelength regions from the EDFA.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] "Linear optical amplifiers" using gain-clamping techniques have been developed.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] High optical nonlinearity makes semiconductor amplifiers attractive for all optical signal processing like all-optical switching and wavelength conversion.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] There has been much research on semiconductor optical amplifiers as elements for optical signal processing, wavelength conversion, clock recovery, signal demultiplexing, and pattern recognition.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] A recent addition to the SOA family is the vertical-cavity SOA (VCSOA).
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] These devices are similar in structure to, and share many features with, vertical-cavity surface-emitting lasers (VCSELs).
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The major difference when comparing VCSOAs and VCSELs is the reduced mirror reflectivity used in the amplifier cavity.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] With VCSOAs, reduced feedback is necessary to prevent the device from reaching lasing threshold.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Due to the extremely short cavity length, and correspondingly thin gain medium, these devices exhibit very low single-pass gain (typically on the order of a few percent) and also a very large free spectral range (FSR).
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The small single-pass gain requires relatively high mirror reflectivity to boost the total signal gain.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] In addition to boosting the total signal gain, the use of the resonant cavity structure results in a very narrow gain bandwidth; coupled with the large FSR of the optical cavity, this effectively limits operation of the VCSOA to single-channel amplification.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Thus, VCSOAs can be seen as amplifying filters.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Given their vertical-cavity geometry, VCSOAs are resonant cavity optical amplifiers that operate with the input/output signal entering/exiting normal to the wafer surface.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] In addition to their small size, the surface normal operation of VCSOAs leads to a number of advantages, including low power consumption, low noise figure, polarization insensitive gain, and the ability to fabricate high fill factor two-dimensional arrays on a single semiconductor chip.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] These devices are still in the early stages of research, though promising preamplifier results have been demonstrated.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Further extensions to VCSOA technology are the demonstration of wavelength tunable devices.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] These MEMS-tunable vertical-cavity SOAs utilize a microelectromechanical systems (MEMS) based tuning mechanism for wide and continuous tuning of the peak gain wavelength of the amplifier.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] SOAs have a more rapid gain response, which is in the order of 1 to 100 ps.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] For high output power and broader wavelength range, tapered amplifiers are used.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] These amplifiers consist of a lateral single-mode section and a section with a tapered structure, where the laser light is amplified.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The tapered structure leads to a reduction of the power density at the output facet.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] In a Raman amplifier, the signal is intensified by Raman amplification.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Unlike the EDFA and SOA the amplification effect is achieved by a nonlinear interaction between the signal and a pump laser within an optical fiber.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] There are two types of Raman amplifier: distributed and lumped.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] A distributed Raman amplifier is one in which the transmission fiber is utilised as the gain medium by multiplexing a pump wavelength with signal wavelength, while a lumped Raman amplifier utilises a dedicated, shorter length of fiber to provide amplification.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] In the case of a lumped Raman amplifier, a highly nonlinear fiber with a small core is utilised to increase the interaction between signal and pump wavelengths, and thereby reduce the length of fiber required.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The pump light may be coupled into the transmission fiber in the same direction as the signal (co-directional pumping), in the opposite direction (contra-directional pumping) or both.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Contra-directional pumping is more common as the transfer of noise from the pump to the signal is reduced.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The pump power required for Raman amplification is higher than that required by the EDFA, with in excess of 500 mW being required to achieve useful levels of gain in a distributed amplifier.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Lumped amplifiers, where the pump light can be safely contained to avoid safety implications of high optical powers, may use over 1 W of optical power.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The principal advantage of Raman amplification is its ability to provide distributed amplification within the transmission fiber, thereby increasing the length of spans between amplifier and regeneration sites.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] The amplification bandwidth of Raman amplifiers is defined by the pump wavelengths utilised and so amplification can be provided over wider, and different, regions than may be possible with other amplifier types which rely on dopants and device design to define the amplification 'window'.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Raman amplifiers have some fundamental advantages.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] First, Raman gain exists in every fiber, which provides a cost-effective means of upgrading from the terminal ends.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Second, the gain is nonresonant, which means that gain is available over the entire transparency region of the fiber ranging from approximately 0.3 to 2 μm.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] A third advantage of Raman amplifiers is that the gain spectrum can be tailored by adjusting the pump wavelengths.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] For instance, multiple pump lines can be used to increase the optical bandwidth, and the pump distribution determines the gain flatness.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Another advantage of Raman amplification is that it is a relatively broad-band amplifier with a bandwidth > 5 THz, and the gain is reasonably flat over a wide wavelength range.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] However, a number of challenges for Raman amplifiers prevented their earlier adoption.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] First, compared to the EDFAs, Raman amplifiers have relatively poor pumping efficiency at lower signal powers.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Although a disadvantage, this lack of pump efficiency also makes gain clamping easier in Raman amplifiers.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Second, Raman amplifiers require a longer gain fiber.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] However, this disadvantage can be mitigated by combining gain and the dispersion compensation in a single fiber.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] A third disadvantage of Raman amplifiers is a fast response time, which gives rise to new sources of noise, as further discussed below.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Finally, there are concerns of nonlinear penalty in the amplifier for the WDM signal channels.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] An optical parametric amplifier allows the amplification of a weak signal-impulse in a nonlinear medium such as a noncentrosymmetric nonlinear medium (e.g.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Beta barium borate (BBO)) or even a standard fused silica optical fiber via the Kerr effect.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] In contrast to the previously mentioned amplifiers, which are mostly used in telecommunication environments, this type finds its main application in expanding the frequency tunability of ultrafast solid-state lasers (e.g.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] By using a noncollinear interaction geometry optical parametric amplifiers are capable of extremely broad amplification bandwidths.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] In the 21st century high power fiber lasers were adopted as an industrial material processing tool, and were expanding into other markets including the medical and scientific markets.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] One key enhancement enabling penetration into the scientific market was improvement in high finesse fiber amplifiers, which became able to deliver single frequency linewidths (<5 kHz) together with excellent beam quality and stable linearly polarized output.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Systems meeting these specifications steadily progressed from a few watts of output power initially, to tens of watts and later hundreds of watts.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] As of 2015 high finesse, high power and pulsed fiber amplifiers delivered power levels exceeding those available from commercial solid-state single-frequency sources, and stable optimized performance, opening up new scientific applications.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] There are several simulation tools that can be used to design optical amplifiers.
[src:photonics/optical-amplifier] Popular commercial tools have been developed by Optiwave Systems and VPI Systems.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] An **optical fiber**, or **optical fibre**, is a flexible glass or plastic fiber that can transmit light from one end to the other.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Such fibers are widely used in fiber-optic communication, where they permit transmission over longer distances and at higher bandwidths (data transfer rates) than electrical cables.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Fibers are used instead of cables because signals travel along them with less loss and are immune to electromagnetic interference.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Fibers are also used for illumination and imaging, and are often wrapped in bundles so they may be used to carry light into, or images out of confined spaces, as in the case of a fiberscope.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Specially designed fibers are also used for a variety of other applications, such as fiber optic sensors and fiber lasers.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Glass optical fibers are typically made by drawing, while plastic fibers can be made either by drawing or by extrusion.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fibers typically include a core surrounded by a transparent cladding material with a lower index of refraction.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Light is kept in the core by the phenomenon of total internal reflection which causes the fiber to act as a waveguide.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Fibers that support many propagation paths or transverse modes are called multi-mode fibers, while those that support a single mode are called single-mode fibers (SMF).
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Multi-mode fibers generally have a wider core diameter and are used for short-distance communication links and for applications where high power must be transmitted.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Single-mode fibers are used for most communication links longer than 1,050 meters (3,440 ft).
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Being able to join optical fibers with low loss is important in fiber optic communication.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] This is more complex than joining electrical wire or cable and involves careful cleaving of the fibers, precise alignment of the fiber cores, and the coupling of these aligned cores.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] For applications that demand a permanent connection a fusion splice is common.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] In this technique, an electric arc is used to melt the ends of the fibers together.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Another common technique is a mechanical splice, where the ends of the fibers are held in contact by mechanical force.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Temporary or semi-permanent connections are made by means of specialized optical fiber connectors.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The field of applied science and engineering concerned with the design and application of optical fibers is known as *fiber optics*.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The term was coined by Indian-American physicist Narinder Singh Kapany.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Daniel Colladon and Jacques Babinet first demonstrated the guiding of light by refraction, the principle that makes fiber optics possible, in Paris in the early 1840s.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] John Tyndall included a demonstration of it in his public lectures in London, 12 years later.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] In the late 19th century, a team of Viennese doctors guided light through bent glass rods to illuminate body cavities.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Practical applications such as close internal illumination during dentistry followed, early in the twentieth century.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Image transmission through tubes was demonstrated independently by the radio experimenter Clarence Hansell and the television pioneer John Logie Baird in the 1920s.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] In the 1930s, Heinrich Lamm showed that one could transmit images through a bundle of unclad optical fibers and used it for internal medical examinations, but his work was largely forgotten.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] In 1953, Dutch scientist Bram van Heel first demonstrated image transmission through bundles of optical fibers with a transparent cladding.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Later that same year, Harold Hopkins and Narinder Singh Kapany at Imperial College in London succeeded in making image-transmitting bundles with over 10,000 fibers, and subsequently achieved image transmission through a 75 cm long bundle which combined several thousand fibers.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The first practical fiber optic semi-flexible gastroscope was patented by Basil Hirschowitz, C.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Curtiss, researchers at the University of Michigan, in 1956.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] In the process of developing the gastroscope, Curtiss produced the first glass-clad fibers; previous optical fibers had relied on air or impractical oils and waxes as the low-index cladding material.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Kapany coined the term *fiber optics* after writing a 1960 article in *Scientific American* that introduced the topic to a wide audience.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] He subsequently wrote the first book about the new field.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The first working fiber-optic data transmission system was demonstrated by German physicist Manfred Börner at Telefunken Research Labs in Ulm in 1965, followed by the first patent application for this technology in 1966.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] In 1968, NASA used fiber optics in the television cameras that were sent to the moon.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] At the time, the use in the cameras was classified *confidential*, and employees handling the cameras had to be supervised by someone with an appropriate security clearance.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Hockham of the British company Standard Telephones and Cables (STC) were the first to promote the idea that the attenuation in optical fibers could be reduced below 20 decibels per kilometer (dB/km), making fibers a practical communication medium, in 1965.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] They proposed that the attenuation in fibers available at the time was caused by impurities that could be removed, rather than by fundamental physical effects such as scattering.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] They correctly and systematically theorized the light-loss properties for optical fiber and pointed out the right material to use for such fibers—silica glass with high purity.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] This discovery earned Kao the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The crucial attenuation limit of 20 dB/km was first achieved in 1970 by researchers Robert D.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Schultz, and Frank Zimar working for American glass maker Corning Glass Works.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] They demonstrated a fiber with 17 dB/km attenuation by doping silica glass with titanium.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] A few years later, they produced a fiber with only 4 dB/km attenuation using germanium dioxide as the core dopant.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] In 1981, General Electric produced fused quartz ingots that could be drawn into strands 25 miles (40 km) long.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Initially, high-quality optical fibers could only be manufactured at two meters per second.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Chemical engineer Thomas Mensah joined Corning in 1983 and increased the speed of manufacture to over 50 meters per second, making optical fiber cables cheaper than traditional copper ones.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] These innovations ushered in the era of optical fiber telecommunication.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The Italian research center CSELT worked with Corning to develop practical optical fiber cables, resulting in the first metropolitan fiber optic cable being deployed in Turin in 1977.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] CSELT also developed an early technique for splicing optical fibers, called Springroove.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Attenuation in modern optical cables is far less than in electrical copper cables, leading to long-haul fiber connections with repeater distances of 70–150 kilometers (43–93 mi).
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Payne of the University of Southampton and Emmanuel Desurvire at Bell Labs, developed the erbium-doped fiber amplifier, which reduced the cost of long-distance fiber systems by reducing or eliminating optical-electrical-optical repeaters, in 1986 and 1987 respectively.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The emerging field of photonic crystals led to the development in 1991 of photonic-crystal fiber, which guides light by diffraction from a periodic structure, rather than by total internal reflection.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The first photonic crystal fibers became commercially available in 2000.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Photonic crystal fibers can carry higher power than conventional fibers and their wavelength-dependent properties can be manipulated to improve performance.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fiber is used as a medium for telecommunication and computer networking because it is flexible and can be bundled as cables.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] It is especially advantageous for long-distance communications, because infrared light propagates through the fiber with much lower attenuation compared to electricity in electrical cables.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] This allows long distances to be spanned with few repeaters.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] A data transfer rate of 10 or 40 Gbit/s is typical in deployed systems.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Using wavelength-division multiplexing (WDM) enables each fiber to carry many independent channels, each using a different wavelength of light.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The net data rate (data rate without overhead bytes) per fiber is the per-channel data rate reduced by the forward error correction (FEC) overhead, multiplied by the number of channels (usually up to 80 in commercial dense WDM systems as of 2008).
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] For short-distance applications, such as a network in an office building (see fiber to the office), fiber-optic cabling can save space in cable ducts.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] This is because a single fiber can carry much more data than electrical cables such as standard category 5 cable, which typically runs at 100 Mbit/s or 1 Gbit/s speeds.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Fibers are often also used for short-distance connections between devices.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] For example, most high-definition televisions offer a digital audio optical connection.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] This allows the streaming of audio over light, using the S/PDIF protocol over an optical TOSLINK connection.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Fiber optic drones have been used in the Russo-Ukrainian War since March 2024.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] These types of drones are immune to electromagnetic interference and are not affected by electronic warfare systems.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The drones typically carry spools of glass fiber-optic cable ranging from 5 to 30 kilometres (3.1 to 18.6 mi) in length, with experimental configurations reported at up to 65 kilometres (40 mi).
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Because the control signals and video feed travel through the glass core at the speed of light without generating radio emissions, the drones cannot be located or disabled by conventional radio-frequency jamming or direction-finding equipment.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Russia's Ushkuynik KVN was among the first mass-produced fiber-optic FPV loitering munitions, deployed from 2024 onward during the Russo-Ukrainian conflict.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] A physical limitation of the technology is cable snagging: if the drone maneuvers sharply through dense terrain, the trailing glass cable can catch on vegetation or structures and snap, immediately ending the mission.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fibers are used as light guides in medical and other applications where bright light needs to be shone on a target without a clear line-of-sight path.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Many microscopes use fiber-optic light sources to provide intense illumination of samples being studied.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] In some buildings, optical fibers route sunlight from the roof to other parts of the building (see nonimaging optics).
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Optical-fiber lamps are used for illumination in decorative applications, including signs, art, toys and artificial Christmas trees.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fiber is an intrinsic part of the light-transmitting concrete building product LiTraCon.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The bundles are led from exterior/rooftop optical light collectors through small openings or cable ducts and carry the light to where it is needed.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The optical fibers end in hybrid luminaires where the sunlight is joined with electric light, either on demand or to automatically maintain a constant light level even as the available sunlight decreases.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Fibers have many uses in remote sensing.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] In some applications, the fiber itself is the sensor (the fibers channel optical light to a processing device that analyzes changes in the light's characteristics).
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] In other cases, fiber is used to connect a sensor to a measurement system.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fibers can be used as sensors to measure strain, temperature, pressure, and other quantities by modifying a fiber so that the property being measured modulates the intensity, phase, polarization, wavelength, or transit time of light in the fiber.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Sensors that vary the intensity of light are the simplest since only a simple source and detector are required.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] A particularly useful feature of such fiber optic sensors is that they can, if required, provide distributed sensing over distances of up to one meter.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Distributed acoustic sensing is one example of this.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fiber can also be used in structural health monitoring.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] This type of sensor can detect stresses that may have a lasting impact on structures.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] It is based on the principle of measuring analog attenuation.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] In contrast, highly localized measurements can be provided by integrating miniaturized sensing elements with the tip of the fiber.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] These can be implemented by various micro- and nanofabrication technologies, such that they do not exceed the microscopic boundary of the fiber tip, allowing for such applications as insertion into blood vessels via hypodermic needle.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Extrinsic fiber optic sensors use an optical fiber cable, normally a multi-mode one, to transmit modulated light from either a non-fiber optical sensor—or an electronic sensor connected to an optical transmitter.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] A major benefit of extrinsic sensors is their ability to reach otherwise inaccessible places.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] An example is the measurement of temperature inside jet engines by using a fiber to transmit radiation into a pyrometer outside the engine.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Extrinsic sensors can be used in the same way to measure the internal temperature of electrical transformers, where the extreme electromagnetic fields present make other measurement techniques impossible.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Extrinsic sensors measure vibration, rotation, displacement, velocity, acceleration, torque, and torsion.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] A solid-state version of the gyroscope, using the interference of light, has been developed.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The fiber optic gyroscope (FOG) has no moving parts and exploits the Sagnac effect to detect mechanical rotation.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Common uses for fiber optic sensors include advanced intrusion detection security systems.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The light is transmitted along a fiber optic sensor cable placed on a fence, pipeline, or communication cabling, and the returned signal is monitored and analyzed for disturbances.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] This return signal is digitally processed to detect disturbances and trip an alarm if an intrusion has occurred.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fibers are widely used as components of optical chemical sensors and optical biosensors.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fiber is also used in imaging optics.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] A coherent bundle of fibers is used, sometimes along with lenses, for a long, thin imaging device called an endoscope, which is used to view objects through a small hole.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Medical endoscopes are used for minimally invasive exploratory or surgical procedures.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Industrial endoscopes (see fiberscope or borescope) are used for inspecting anything hard to reach, such as jet engine interiors.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fiber can be used to transmit power using a photovoltaic cell to convert the light into electricity.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] While this method of power transmission is not as efficient as conventional ones, it is especially useful in situations where it is desirable not to have a metallic conductor as in the case of use near MRI machines, which produce strong magnetic fields.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Other examples are for powering electronics in high-powered antenna elements and measurement devices used in high-voltage transmission equipment.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] In spectroscopy, optical fiber bundles transmit light from a spectrometer to a substance that cannot be placed inside the spectrometer itself, in order to analyze its composition.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] A spectrometer analyzes substances by bouncing light off and through them.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] By using fibers, a spectrometer can be used to study objects remotely.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] An optical fiber doped with certain rare-earth elements such as erbium can be used as the gain medium of a fiber laser or optical amplifier.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Rare-earth-doped optical fibers can be used to provide signal amplification by splicing a short section of doped fiber into a regular (undoped) optical fiber line.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The doped fiber is optically pumped with a second laser wavelength that is coupled into the line in addition to the signal wave.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Both wavelengths of light are transmitted through the doped fiber, which transfers energy from the second pump wavelength to the signal wave.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The process that causes the amplification is stimulated emission.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fiber is also widely exploited as a nonlinear medium.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The glass medium supports a host of nonlinear optical interactions, and the long interaction lengths possible in fiber facilitate a variety of phenomena, which are harnessed for applications and fundamental investigation.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Conversely, fiber nonlinearity can have deleterious effects on optical signals, and measures are often required to minimize such unwanted effects.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fibers doped with a wavelength shifter collect scintillation light in physics experiments.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Fiber-optic sights for handguns, rifles, and shotguns use pieces of optical fiber to improve the visibility of markings on the sight.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fibers are used as components in e-textiles.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] This was first done by Harry Wainwright in the 1980s.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] An optical fiber is a cylindrical dielectric waveguide (nonconducting waveguide) that transmits light along its axis through the process of total internal reflection.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The fiber consists of a *core* surrounded by a cladding layer, both of which are made of dielectric materials.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] To confine the optical signal in the core, the refractive index of the core must be greater than that of the cladding.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The boundary between the core and cladding may either be abrupt, in *step-index fiber*, or gradual, in *graded-index fiber*.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Light can be fed into optical fibers using lasers or LEDs.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fibers are immune to electrical interference as there is no cross-talk between signals in different cables and no pickup of environmental noise.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Information traveling inside the optical fiber is even immune to electromagnetic pulses generated by nuclear devices.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Fiber cables do not conduct electricity, which makes them useful for protecting communications equipment in high voltage environments such as power generation facilities or applications prone to lightning strikes.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The electrical isolation also prevents problems with ground loops.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Because there is no electricity in optical cables that could potentially generate sparks, they can be used in environments where explosive fumes are present.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Wiretapping (in this case, fiber tapping) is more difficult compared to electrical connections.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Fiber cables are not targeted for metal theft.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] In contrast, copper cable systems use large amounts of copper and have been targeted since the 2000s commodities boom.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The refractive index is a way of measuring the speed of light in a material.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Light travels fastest in a vacuum, such as in outer space.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The speed of light in vacuum is about 300,000 kilometers (186,000 miles) per second.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The refractive index of a medium is calculated by dividing the speed of light in vacuum by the speed of light in that medium.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The refractive index of vacuum is therefore 1, by definition.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] A typical single-mode fiber used for telecommunications has a cladding made of pure silica, with an index of 1.444 at 1500 nm, and a core of doped silica with an index around 1.4475.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The larger the index of refraction, the slower light travels in that medium.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] From this information, a simple rule of thumb is that a signal using optical fiber for communication will travel at around 200,000 kilometers per second.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Thus a phone call carried by fiber between Sydney and New York, a 16,000-kilometer distance, means that there is a minimum delay of 80 milliseconds (about ${\tfrac {1}{12}}$ of a second) between when one caller speaks and the other hears.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] When light traveling in an optically dense medium hits a boundary at a steep angle of incidence (larger than the critical angle for the boundary), the light is completely reflected.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] This is called total internal reflection.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] This effect is used in optical fibers to confine light in the core.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Most modern optical fiber is *weakly guiding*, meaning that the difference in refractive index between the core and the cladding is very small (typically less than 1%).
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Light travels through the fiber core, bouncing back and forth off the boundary between the core and cladding.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Because the light must strike the boundary with an angle greater than the critical angle, only light that enters the fiber within a certain range of angles can travel down the fiber without leaking out.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] This range of angles is called the acceptance cone of the fiber.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] There is a maximum angle from the fiber axis at which light may enter the fiber so that it will propagate, or travel, in the core of the fiber.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The sine of this maximum angle is the numerical aperture (NA) of the fiber.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Fiber with a larger NA requires less precision to splice and work with than fiber with a smaller NA.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The size of this acceptance cone is a function of the refractive index difference between the fiber's core and cladding.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fibers with a large core diameter (greater than 10 micrometers) may be analyzed by geometrical optics.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Such fibers are called *multi-mode fibers*, from the electromagnetic analysis (see below).
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] In a step-index multi-mode fiber, rays of light are guided along the fiber core by total internal reflection.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Rays that meet the core-cladding boundary at an angle (measured relative to a line normal to the boundary) greater than the critical angle for this boundary, are completely reflected.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The critical angle is determined by the difference in the index of refraction between the core and cladding materials.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Rays that meet the boundary at a low angle are refracted from the core into the cladding where they terminate.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The critical angle determines the acceptance angle of the fiber, often reported as a numerical aperture.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] A high numerical aperture allows light to propagate down the fiber in rays both close to the axis and at various angles, allowing efficient coupling of light into the fiber.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] However, this high numerical aperture increases the amount of dispersion as rays at different angles have different path lengths and therefore take different amounts of time to traverse the fiber.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] In graded-index fiber, the index of refraction in the core decreases continuously between the axis and the cladding.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] This causes light rays to bend smoothly as they approach the cladding, rather than reflecting abruptly from the core-cladding boundary.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The resulting curved paths reduce multi-path dispersion because high-angle rays pass more through the lower-index periphery of the core, rather than the high-index center.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The index profile is chosen to minimize the difference in axial propagation speeds of the various rays in the fiber.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] This ideal index profile is very close to a parabolic relationship between the index and the distance from the axis.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Fibers with a core diameter less than about ten times the wavelength of the propagating light cannot be modeled using geometric optics.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Instead, they must be analyzed as an electromagnetic waveguide structure, according to Maxwell's equations as reduced to the electromagnetic wave equation.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] As an optical waveguide, the fiber supports one or more confined transverse modes by which light can propagate along the fiber.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Fiber supporting only one mode is called *single-mode*.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The waveguide analysis shows that the light energy in the fiber is not completely confined in the core.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Instead, especially in single-mode fibers, a significant fraction of the energy in the bound mode travels in the cladding as an evanescent wave.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The most common type of single-mode fiber has a core diameter of 8–10 micrometers and is designed for use in the near infrared.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Multi-mode fiber, by comparison, is manufactured with core diameters as small as 50 micrometers and as large as hundreds of micrometers.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Some special-purpose optical fiber is constructed with a non-cylindrical core or cladding layer, usually with an elliptical or rectangular cross-section.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] These include polarization-maintaining fiber used in fiber optic sensors and fiber designed to suppress whispering gallery mode propagation.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Photonic-crystal fiber is made with a regular pattern of index variation (often in the form of cylindrical holes that run along the length of the fiber).
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Such fiber uses diffraction effects instead of or in addition to total internal reflection, to confine light to the fiber's core.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The properties of the fiber can be tailored to a wide variety of applications.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Attenuation in fiber optics, also known as transmission loss, is the reduction in the intensity of the light signal as it travels through the transmission medium.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Attenuation coefficients in fiber optics are usually expressed in units of dB/km.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The medium is usually a fiber of silica glass that confines the incident light beam within.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Attenuation is an important factor limiting the transmission of a digital signal across large distances.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Thus, much research has gone into both limiting the attenuation and maximizing the amplification of the optical signal.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Single-mode optical fibers can be made with extremely low loss.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Corning's Vascade® EX2500 fiber, a low loss single-mode fiber for telecommunications wavelengths, has a nominal attenuation of 0.148 dB/km at 1550 nm.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] A 10 km length of such fiber transmits nearly 71% of optical energy at 1550 nm.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Attenuation in optical fiber is caused primarily by both scattering and absorption.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] In fibers based on fluoride glasses such as ZBLAN, minimum attenuation is limited by impurity absorption.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The vast majority of optical fibers are based on silica glass, where impurity absorption is negligible.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] In silica fibers attenuation is determined by intrinsic mechanisms: Rayleigh scattering and infrared absorption in the glasses through which the light is propagating.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Absorption in silica increases steeply at wavelengths above 1570 nm.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] At wavelengths most useful for telecommunications, Rayleigh scattering is the dominant loss mechanism.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] At 1550 nm attenuation components for a record low loss fiber are given as follows: Rayleigh scattering loss: 0.1200 dB/km, infrared absorption loss: 0.0150 dB/km, impurity absorption loss: 0.0047 dB/km, waveguide imperfection loss: 0.0010 dB/km.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The propagation of light through the core of an optical fiber is based on the total internal reflection of the lightwave, in terms of geometric optics, or guided modes, in terms of electromagnetic waveguide.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] In a typical single mode optical fiber about 75% of light is propagating through the core material, having higher refractive index, and about 25% of light is propagating through the cladding, having lower refractive index.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The interface between the core and cladding glasses is exceptionally smooth and does not give rise to a significant scattering loss or a waveguide imperfection loss.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The scattering loss originates primarily from the Rayleigh scattering in the bulk of the glasses composing the fiber core and cladding.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The scattering of light in optical quality glass fiber is caused by molecular level irregularities (compositional fluctuations) in the glass structure.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Indeed, one emerging school of thought is that glass is simply the limiting case of a polycrystalline solid.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Within this framework, *domains* exhibiting various degrees of short-range order become the building blocks of metals as well as glasses and ceramics.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Distributed both between and within these domains are micro-structural defects that provide the most ideal locations for light scattering.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Scattering depends on the wavelength of the light being scattered and on the size of the scattering centers.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Angular dependence of the light intensity scattered from an optical fiber matched that of Rayleigh scattering, indicating that the scattering centers are much smaller than the wavelength of propagating light.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] It originates from the density fluctuations driven by fictive temperature of the glass, and from the concentration fluctuations of dopants in both the core and the cladding.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Rayleigh scattering coefficient, *R*, can be presented as : $R=R_{\text{d}}+R_{\text{c}}$ where *R*d represents Rayleigh scattering on density fluctuations and *R*c represents Rayleigh scattering on dopant concentration fluctuations.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The only physically significant variable affecting scattering on density fluctuations is the fictive temperature of the glass, lower fictive temperature results in a more homogeneous glass and lower Rayleigh scattering.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Fictive temperature may be dramatically reduced by about 100 wt. ppm of alkali oxide dopant in the fiber core, as well as slower cooling of the fiber during the fiber draw process.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] These approaches are used to produce optical fibers with the lowest attenuation, especially those for submarine telecom cables.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] For small dopant concentrations, *R*c is proportional to *x*(d*n*/d*x*)2, where x is the mole fraction of the dopant in SiO2-based glass and n is the refractive index of the glass.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] When GeO2 dopant is used to increase the refractive index of the fiber core, it increases the concentration fluctuation component of Rayleigh scattering, and attenuation of the fiber.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] This is why the lowest attenuation fibers do not use GeO2 in the core, and use fluorine in the cladding, to reduce the refractive index of the cladding.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] *R*c in pure silica core fiber is proportional to the overlap integral between LP01 mode and fluorine-induced concentration fluctuation component in the cladding.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] In the core of potassium-doped pure silica-core (KPSC) fiber only density fluctuations play a significant role, as the concentrations of K2O, fluorine and chlorine are very low.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The density fluctuations in the core are moderated by lower fictive temperature resulting from potassium doping, and are further reduced by annealing during the fiber draw process.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] This differs from the cladding, where higher fluorine dopant levels and the resulting concentration fluctuations add to the loss.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] In such fibers the light travelling through the core experiences lower scattering and lower attenuation compared to the light propagating through the cladding segment of the fiber.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] At high optical powers, scattering can also be caused by nonlinear optical processes in the fiber.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] In addition to light scattering, attenuation or signal loss can also occur due to selective absorption of specific wavelengths.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The design of any optically transparent device requires the selection of materials based upon knowledge of its properties and limitations.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The crystal structure absorption characteristics observed at the lower frequency regions (mid- to far-IR wavelength range) define the long-wavelength transparency limit of the material.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] They are the result of the interactive coupling between the motions of thermally induced vibrations of the constituent atoms and molecules of the solid lattice and the incident light wave radiation.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Hence, all materials are bounded by limiting regions of absorption caused by atomic and molecular vibrations (bond-stretching) in the far-infrared (>10 μm).
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] In other words, the selective absorption of IR light by a particular material occurs because the selected frequency of the light wave matches the frequency (or an integer multiple of the frequency, i.e. harmonic) at which the particles of that material vibrate.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Since different atoms and molecules have different natural frequencies of vibration, they will selectively absorb different frequencies (or portions of the spectrum) of IR light.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Reflection and transmission of light waves occur because the frequencies of the light waves do not match the natural resonant frequencies of vibration of the objects.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] When IR light of these frequencies strikes an object, the energy is either reflected or transmitted.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Attenuation over a cable run is significantly increased by the inclusion of connectors and splices.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Connectors typically introduce 0.3 dB per connector on well-polished connectors.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] Splices typically introduce less than 0.2 dB per splice.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] where the dB loss per kilometer is a function of the type of fiber and can be found in the manufacturer's specifications.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] For example, a typical 1550 nm single-mode fiber has a loss of 0.3 dB per kilometer.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p01] The calculated loss budget is used when testing to confirm that the measured loss is within the normal operating parameters.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Glass optical fibers are almost always made from silica, but some other materials, such as fluorozirconate, fluoroaluminate, and chalcogenide glasses as well as crystalline materials like sapphire, are used for longer-wavelength infrared or other specialized applications.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Silica and fluoride glasses usually have refractive indices of about 1.5, but some materials such as the chalcogenides can have indices as high as 3.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Typically the index difference between core and cladding is less than one percent.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Plastic optical fibers (POF) are commonly step-index multi-mode fibers with a core diameter of 0.5 millimeters or larger.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] POF typically have higher attenuation coefficients than glass fibers, 1 dB/m or higher, and this high attenuation limits the range of POF-based systems.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Silica exhibits fairly good optical transmission over a wide range of wavelengths.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] In the near-infrared (near IR) portion of the spectrum, particularly around 1.5 μm, silica can have extremely low absorption and scattering losses of the order of 0.2 dB/km.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Such low losses depend on using ultra-pure silica.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] A high transparency in the 1.4-μm region is achieved by maintaining a low concentration of hydroxyl groups (OH).
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Alternatively, a high OH concentration is better for transmission in the ultraviolet (UV) region.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Silica can be drawn into fibers at reasonably high temperatures and has a fairly broad glass transformation range.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] One other advantage is that fusion splicing and cleaving of silica fibers is relatively effective.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Silica fiber also has high mechanical strength against both pulling and even bending, provided that the fiber is not too thick and that the surfaces have been well prepared during processing.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Even simple cleaving of the ends of the fiber can provide nicely flat surfaces with acceptable optical quality.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Silica is also relatively chemically inert.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] In particular, it is not hygroscopic (does not absorb water).
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Silica glass can be doped with various materials.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] One purpose of doping is to raise the refractive index (e.g. with germanium dioxide (GeO2) or aluminium oxide (Al2O3)) or to lower it (e.g. with fluorine or boron trioxide (B2O3)).
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Doping is also possible with laser-active ions (for example, rare-earth-doped fibers) in order to obtain active fibers to be used, for example, in fiber amplifiers or laser applications.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Both the fiber core and cladding are typically doped, so that the entire assembly (core and cladding) is effectively the same compound (e.g. an aluminosilicate, germanosilicate, phosphosilicate or borosilicate glass).
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Particularly for active fibers, pure silica is usually not a very suitable host glass, because it exhibits a low solubility for rare-earth ions.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] This can lead to quenching effects due to the clustering of dopant ions.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Aluminosilicates are much more effective in this respect.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Silica fiber also exhibits a high threshold for optical damage.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] This property ensures a low tendency for laser-induced breakdown.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] This is important for fiber amplifiers when utilized for the amplification of short pulses.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Because of these properties, silica fibers are the material of choice in many optical applications, such as communications (except for very short distances with plastic optical fiber), fiber lasers, fiber amplifiers, and fiber-optic sensors.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Large efforts put forth in the development of various types of silica fibers have further increased the performance of such fibers over other materials.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Fluoride glass is a class of non-oxide optical quality glasses composed of fluorides of various metals.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Because of the low viscosity of these glasses, it is very difficult to completely avoid crystallization while processing it through the glass transition (or drawing the fiber from the melt).
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Thus, although heavy metal fluoride glasses (HMFG) exhibit very low optical attenuation, they are not only difficult to manufacture, but are quite fragile, and have poor resistance to moisture and other environmental attacks.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Their best attribute is that they lack the absorption band associated with the hydroxyl (OH) group (3,200–3,600 cm−1; i.e., 2,777–3,125 nm or 2.78–3.13 μm), which is present in nearly all oxide-based glasses.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Such low losses were never realized in practice, and the fragility and high cost of fluoride fibers made them less than ideal as primary candidates.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Fluoride fibers are used in mid-IR spectroscopy, fiber optic sensors, thermometry, and imaging.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Fluoride fibers can be used for guided lightwave transmission in media such as YAG (yttrium aluminium garnet) lasers at 2.9 μm, as required for medical applications (e.g. ophthalmology and dentistry).
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] An example of a heavy metal fluoride glass is the ZBLAN glass group, composed of zirconium, barium, lanthanum, aluminium, and sodium fluorides.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Their main technological application is as optical waveguides in both planar and fiber forms.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] They are advantageous especially in the mid-infrared (2,000–5,000 nm) range.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Phosphate glass is a class of optical glasses composed of metaphosphates of various metals.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Instead of the SiO4 tetrahedra in the network solid structure of silicate glasses, the building block for this glass is phosphorus pentoxide (P2O5), which crystallizes in at least four different forms.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The most familiar polymorph is the cagelike structure of P4O10.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Phosphate glasses can be advantageous over silica glasses for optical fibers with a high concentration of doping rare-earth ions.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] A mix of fluoride glass and phosphate glass is fluorophosphate glass.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The chalcogens—the elements in group 16 of the periodic table—particularly sulfur (S), selenium (Se) and tellurium (Te)—react with more electropositive elements, such as silver, to form chalcogenides.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] These are extremely versatile compounds, in that they can be crystalline or amorphous, metallic or semiconducting, and conductors of ions or electrons.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Chalcogenide glass can be used to make fibers for far infrared transmission.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Standard optical fibers are made by first constructing a large-diameter *preform* with a carefully controlled refractive index profile, and then *pulling* the preform to form the long, thin optical fiber.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The preform is commonly made by three chemical vapor deposition methods: *inside vapor deposition*, *outside vapor deposition*, and *vapor axial deposition*.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] With *inside vapor deposition*, the preform starts as a hollow glass tube approximately 40 centimeters (16 in) long, which is placed horizontally and rotated slowly on a lathe.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Gases such as silicon tetrachloride (SiCl4) or germanium tetrachloride (GeCl4) are injected with oxygen in the end of the tube.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The gases are then heated by means of an external hydrogen burner, bringing the temperature of the gas up to 1,900 K (1,600 °C, 3,000 °F), where the tetrachlorides react with oxygen to produce silica or germanium dioxide particles.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] When the reaction conditions are chosen to allow this reaction to occur in the gas phase throughout the tube volume, in contrast to earlier techniques where the reaction occurred only on the glass surface, this technique is called *modified chemical vapor deposition*.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The oxide particles then agglomerate to form large particle chains, which subsequently deposit on the walls of the tube as soot.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The deposition is due to the large difference in temperature between the gas core and the wall causing the gas to push the particles outward in a process known as thermophoresis.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The torch is then traversed up and down the length of the tube to deposit the material evenly.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] After the torch has reached the end of the tube, it is then brought back to the beginning of the tube and the deposited particles are then melted to form a solid layer.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] This process is repeated until a sufficient amount of material has been deposited.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] For each layer the composition can be modified by varying the gas composition, resulting in precise control of the finished fiber's optical properties.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] In outside vapor deposition or vapor axial deposition, the glass is formed by *flame hydrolysis*, a reaction in which silicon tetrachloride and germanium tetrachloride are oxidized by reaction with water in an oxyhydrogen flame.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] In outside vapor deposition, the glass is deposited onto a solid rod, which is removed before further processing.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] In vapor axial deposition, a short *seed rod* is used, and a porous preform, whose length is not limited by the size of the source rod, is built up on its end.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The porous preform is consolidated into a transparent, solid preform by heating to about 1,800 K (1,500 °C, 2,800 °F).
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Typical communications fiber uses a circular preform.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] For some applications such as double-clad fibers another form is preferred.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] In fiber lasers based on double-clad fiber, an asymmetric shape improves the filling factor for laser pumping.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Because of the surface tension, the shape is smoothed during the drawing process, and the shape of the resulting fiber does not reproduce the sharp edges of the preform.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Nevertheless, careful polishing of the preform is important, since any defects of the preform surface affect the optical and mechanical properties of the resulting fiber.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The preform, regardless of construction, is placed in a device known as a drawing tower, where the preform tip is heated and the optical fiber is pulled out as a string.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The tension on the fiber can be controlled to maintain the desired fiber thickness.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The light is guided down the core of the fiber by an optical cladding with a lower refractive index that traps light in the core through total internal reflection.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] For some types of fiber, the cladding is made of glass and is drawn along with the core from a preform with radially varying index of refraction.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] For other types of fiber, the cladding is made of plastic and is applied like a coating (see below).
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The cladding is coated by a buffer, (not to be confused with an actual buffer tube), that protects it from moisture and physical damage.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] These coatings are UV-cured urethane acrylate composite or polyimide materials applied to the outside of the fiber during the drawing process.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The coatings protect the very delicate strands of glass fiber—about the size of a human hair—and allow it to survive the rigors of manufacturing, proof testing, cabling, and installation.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The buffer coating must be stripped off the fiber for termination or splicing.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Today's glass optical fiber draw processes employ a dual-layer coating approach.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] An inner primary coating is designed to act as a shock absorber to minimize attenuation caused by microbending.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] An outer secondary coating protects the primary coating against mechanical damage and acts as a barrier to lateral forces, and may be colored to differentiate strands in bundled cable constructions.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] These fiber optic coating layers are applied during the fiber draw, at speeds approaching 100 kilometers per hour (60 mph).
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Fiber optic coatings are applied using one of two methods: *wet-on-dry* and *wet-on-wet*.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] In wet-on-dry, the fiber passes through a primary coating application, which is then UV cured, then through the secondary coating application, which is subsequently cured.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] In wet-on-wet, the fiber passes through both the primary and secondary coating applications, then goes to UV curing.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The thickness of the coating is taken into account when calculating the stress that the fiber experiences under different bend configurations.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] In a two-point bend configuration, a coated fiber is bent in a U-shape and placed between the grooves of two faceplates, which are brought together until the fiber breaks.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The stress in the fiber in this configuration is given by $\sigma =1.198E{d_{\text{f}} \over d-d_{\text{c}}},$ where d is the distance between the faceplates.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The coefficient 1.198 is a geometric constant associated with this configuration.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Fiber optic coatings protect the glass fibers from scratches that could lead to strength degradation.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The combination of moisture and scratches accelerates the aging and deterioration of fiber strength.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] When fiber is subjected to low stresses over a long period, fiber fatigue can occur.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Over time or in extreme conditions, these factors combine to cause microscopic flaws in the glass fiber to propagate, which can ultimately result in fiber failure.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Three key characteristics of fiber optic waveguides can be affected by environmental conditions: strength, attenuation, and resistance to losses caused by microbending.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] External optical fiber cable jackets and buffer tubes protect glass optical fiber from environmental conditions that can affect the fiber's performance and long-term durability.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] On the inside, coatings ensure the reliability of the signal being carried and help minimize attenuation due to microbending.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] In practical fibers, the cladding is usually coated with a tough resin and features an additional *buffer* layer, which may be further surrounded by a *jacket* layer, usually plastic.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] These layers add strength to the fiber but do not affect its optical properties.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Rigid fiber assemblies sometimes put light-absorbing glass between the fibers, to prevent light that leaks out of one fiber from entering another.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] This reduces crosstalk between the fibers, or reduces flare in fiber bundle imaging applications.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Multi-fiber cable usually uses colored buffers to identify each strand.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Modern cables come in a wide variety of sheathings and armor, designed for applications such as direct burial in trenches, high voltage isolation, dual use as power lines, installation in conduit, lashing to aerial telephone poles, submarine installation, and insertion in paved streets.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Some fiber optic cable versions are reinforced with aramid yarns or glass yarns as an intermediary strength member.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] In commercial terms, usage of the glass yarns are more cost-effective with no loss of mechanical durability.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Glass yarns also protect the cable core against rodents and termites.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Fiber cable can be very flexible, but traditional fiber's loss increases greatly if the fiber is bent with a radius smaller than around 30 mm.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] This creates a problem when the cable is bent around corners.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] *Bendable fibers*, targeted toward easier installation in home environments, have been standardized as ITU-T G.657.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] This type of fiber can be bent with a radius as low as 7.5 mm without adverse impact.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Even more bendable fibers have been developed.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Bendable fiber may also be resistant to fiber hacking, in which the signal in a fiber is surreptitiously monitored by bending the fiber and detecting the leakage.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Another important feature of cable is cable's ability to withstand tension which determines how much force can be applied to the cable during installation.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Optical fibers are connected to terminal equipment by optical fiber connectors.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] These connectors are usually of a standard type such as *FC*, *SC*, *ST*, *LC*, *MTRJ*, *MPO* or *SMA*.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Optical fibers may be connected by connectors typically on a patch panel, or permanently by splicing, that is, joining two fibers together to form a continuous optical waveguide.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The generally accepted splicing method is fusion splicing, which melts the fiber ends together.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] For quicker fastening jobs, a *mechanical splice* is used.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] All splicing techniques involve installing an enclosure that protects the splice.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Fusion splicing is done with a specialized instrument.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The fiber ends are first stripped of their protective polymer coating (as well as the more sturdy outer jacket, if present).
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The ends are cleaved with a precision cleaver to make them perpendicular, and are placed into special holders in the fusion splicer.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The splice is usually inspected via a magnified viewing screen to check the cleaves before and fusion after the splice.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The splicer uses small motors to align the end faces together, and emits a small spark between electrodes at the gap to burn off dust and moisture.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Then the splicer generates a larger spark that raises the temperature above the melting point of the glass, fusing the ends permanently.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The location and energy of the spark is carefully controlled so that the molten core and cladding do not mix, and this minimizes optical loss.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] A splice loss estimate is measured by the splicer by directing light through the cladding on one side and measuring the light leaking from the cladding on the other side.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The complexity of this process makes fiber splicing much more difficult than splicing copper wire.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Mechanical fiber splices are designed to be quicker and easier to install, but there is still the need for stripping, careful cleaning, and precision cleaving.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The fiber ends are aligned and held together by a precision sleeve, often using a clear index-matching gel that enhances the transmission of light across the joint.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Mechanical splices typically have a higher optical loss and are less robust than fusion splices, especially if the gel is used.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Fibers are terminated in connectors that hold the fiber end precisely and securely.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] An optical fiber connector is a rigid cylindrical barrel surrounded by a sleeve that holds the barrel in its mating socket.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The mating mechanism can be *push and click*, *turn and latch* (*bayonet mount*), or *screw-in* (*threaded*).
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The barrel is typically free to move within the sleeve and may have a key that prevents the barrel and fiber from rotating as the connectors are mated.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] A typical connector is installed by preparing the fiber end and inserting it into the rear of the connector body.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Quick-set adhesive is usually used to hold the fiber securely, and a strain relief is secured to the rear.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Once the adhesive sets, the fiber's end is polished.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Various polish profiles are used, depending on the type of fiber and the application.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The resulting signal strength loss is called *gap loss*.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] For single-mode fiber, fiber ends are typically polished with a slight curvature that makes the mated connectors touch only at their cores.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] This is called a *physical contact* (PC) polish.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The curved surface may be polished at an angle, to make an *angled physical contact (APC)* connection.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Such connections have higher loss than PC connections but greatly reduced back reflection because light that reflects from the angled surface leaks out of the fiber core.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] APC fiber ends have low back reflection even when disconnected.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] In the 1990s, the number of parts per connector, polishing of the fibers, and the need to oven-bake the epoxy in each connector made terminating fiber optic cables difficult.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Today, connector types on the market offer easier, less labor-intensive ways of terminating cables.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Some of the most popular connectors are pre-polished at the factory and include a gel inside the connector.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] A cleave is made at a required length, to get as close to the polished piece already inside the connector.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The gel surrounds the point where the two pieces meet inside the connector for very little light loss.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] For the most demanding installations, factory pre-polished pigtails of sufficient length to reach the first fusion splice enclosure assures good performance and minimizes on-site labor.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] It is often necessary to align an optical fiber with another optical fiber or with an optoelectronic device such as a light-emitting diode, a laser diode, or a modulator.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] This can involve either carefully aligning the fiber and placing it in contact with the device, or can use a lens to allow coupling over an air gap.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Typically the size of the fiber mode is much larger than the size of the mode in a laser diode or a silicon optical chip.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] In this case, a tapered or lensed fiber is used to match the fiber mode field distribution to that of the other element.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The lens on the end of the fiber can be formed using polishing, laser cutting or fusion splicing.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] In a laboratory environment, a bare fiber end is coupled using a fiber launch system, which uses a microscope objective lens to focus the light down to a fine point.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] A precision translation stage (micro-positioning table) is used to move the lens, fiber, or device to allow the coupling efficiency to be optimized.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Fibers with a connector on the end make this process much simpler: the connector is simply plugged into a pre-aligned fiber-optic collimator, which contains a lens that is either accurately positioned to the fiber or is adjustable.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] To achieve the best injection efficiency into a single-mode fiber, the direction, position, size, and divergence of the beam must all be optimized.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] With good optimization, 70 to 90% coupling efficiency can be achieved.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] With properly polished single-mode fibers, the emitted beam has an almost perfect Gaussian shape—even in the far field—if a good lens is used.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The lens needs to be large enough to support the full numerical aperture of the fiber, and must not introduce aberrations in the beam.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] At optical intensities above two megawatts per square centimeter, when a fiber is subjected to a shock or is otherwise suddenly damaged, a *fiber fuse* can occur.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The reflection from the damage vaporizes the fiber immediately before the break, and this new defect remains reflective so that the damage propagates back toward the transmitter at 1–3 meters per second (4–11 km/h, 2–8 mph).
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The open fiber control system, which ensures laser eye safety in the event of a broken fiber, can also effectively halt propagation of the fiber fuse.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] In situations, such as undersea cables, where high power levels might be used without the need for open fiber control, a fiber fuse protection device at the transmitter can break the circuit to minimize damage.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] The refractive index of fibers varies slightly with the frequency of light, and light sources are not perfectly monochromatic.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Chromatic dispersion arises from both the waveguide structure of the fiber and the dispersive properties of the glass itself, with the latter contribution typically being dominant.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] Modulation of the light source to transmit a signal also slightly widens the frequency band of the transmitted light.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] This has the effect that, over long distances and at high modulation speeds, different portions of light can take different times to arrive at the receiver, ultimately making the signal impossible to discern.
[src:photonics/optical-fiber-p02] This problem can be overcome in several ways, including the use of extra repeaters and the use of a relatively short length of fiber that has the opposite refractive index gradient.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] A **photonic crystal** is an optical nanostructure in which the refractive index changes periodically.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] This affects the propagation of light in the same way that the structure of natural crystals gives rise to X-ray diffraction and that the atomic lattices (crystal structure) of semiconductors affect their conductivity of electrons.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Photonic crystals occur in nature in the form of structural coloration and animal reflectors, and, as artificially produced, promise to be useful in a range of applications.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Photonic crystals can be fabricated for one, two, or three dimensions.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] One-dimensional photonic crystals can be made of thin film layers deposited on each other.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Two-dimensional ones can be made by photolithography, or by drilling holes in a suitable substrate.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Fabrication methods for three-dimensional ones include drilling under different angles, stacking multiple 2-D layers on top of each other, direct laser writing, or, for example, instigating self-assembly of spheres in a matrix and dissolving the spheres.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Photonic crystals can, in principle, find uses wherever light must be manipulated.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] For example, dielectric mirrors are one-dimensional photonic crystals which can produce ultra-high reflectivity mirrors at a specified wavelength.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Two-dimensional photonic crystals called photonic-crystal fibers are used for fiber-optic communication, among other applications.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Three-dimensional crystals may one day be used in optical computers, and could lead to more efficient photovoltaic cells.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Although the energy of light (and all electromagnetic radiation) is quantized in units called photons, the analysis of photonic crystals requires only classical physics.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] "Photonic" in the name is a reference to photonics, a modern designation for the study of light (optics) and optical engineering.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Indeed, the first research into what we now call photonic crystals may have been as early as 1887 when the English physicist Lord Rayleigh experimented with periodic multi-layer dielectric stacks, showing they can effect a photonic band-gap in one dimension.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Research interest grew with work in 1987 by Eli Yablonovitch and Sajeev John on periodic optical structures with more than one dimension—now called photonic crystals.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Photonic crystals contain regularly repeating regions of high and low refractive index.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Light waves may propagate through this structure or propagation may be disallowed, depending on their wavelength.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Wavelengths that may propagate in a given direction are called *modes*, and the ranges of wavelengths which propagate are called *bands*.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Disallowed bands of wavelengths are called *photonic band gaps*.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] This gives rise to distinct optical phenomena, such as inhibition of spontaneous emission, high-reflecting omni-directional mirrors, and low-loss-waveguiding.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] The bandgap of photonic crystals can be understood as the destructive interference of multiple reflections of light propagating in the crystal at each interface between layers of high- and low- refractive index regions, akin to the bandgaps of electrons in solids.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] There are two strategies for opening up the complete photonic band gap.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] The first one is to increase the refractive index contrast for the band gap in each direction becomes wider and the second one is to make the Brillouin zone more similar to sphere.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] However, the former is limited by the available technologies and materials and the latter is restricted by the crystallographic restriction theorem.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] For this reason, the photonic crystals with a complete band gap demonstrated to date have face-centered cubic lattice with the most spherical Brillouin zone and made of high-refractive-index semiconductor materials.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Another approach is to exploit quasicrystalline structures with no crystallography limits.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] A complete photonic bandgap was reported for low-index polymer quasicrystalline samples manufactured by 3D printing.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] The periodicity of the photonic crystal structure must be around or greater than half the wavelength (in the medium) of the light waves in order for interference effects to be exhibited.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Visible light ranges in wavelength between about 400 nm (violet) to about 700 nm (red) and the resulting wavelength inside a material requires dividing that by the average index of refraction.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] The repeating regions of high and low dielectric constant must, therefore, be fabricated at this scale.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] In one dimension, this is routinely accomplished using the techniques of thin-film deposition.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Photonic crystals have been studied in one form or another since 1887, but no one used the term *photonic crystal* until over 100 years later—after Eli Yablonovitch and Sajeev John published two milestone papers on photonic crystals in 1987.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] The early history is well-documented in the form of a story when it was identified as one of the landmark developments in physics by the American Physical Society.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Before 1987, one-dimensional photonic crystals in the form of periodic multi-layer dielectric stacks (such as the Bragg mirror) were studied extensively.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Lord Rayleigh started their study in 1887, by showing that such systems have a one-dimensional photonic band-gap, a spectral range of large reflectivity, known as a *stop-band*.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Today, such structures are used in a diverse range of applications—from reflective coatings to enhancing LED efficiency to highly reflective mirrors in certain laser cavities (see, for example, VCSEL).
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] The pass-bands and stop-bands in photonic crystals were first reduced to practice by Melvin M.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] A detailed theoretical study of one-dimensional optical structures was performed by Vladimir P.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Bykov, who was the first to investigate the effect of a photonic band-gap on the spontaneous emission from atoms and molecules embedded within the photonic structure.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Bykov also speculated as to what could happen if two- or three-dimensional periodic optical structures were used.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] The concept of three-dimensional photonic crystals was then discussed by Ohtaka in 1979, who also developed a formalism for the calculation of the photonic band structure.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] However, these ideas did not take off until after the publication of two milestone papers in 1987 by Yablonovitch and John.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Both these papers concerned high-dimensional periodic optical structures, i.e., photonic crystals.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Yablonovitch's main goal was to engineer photonic density of states to control the spontaneous emission of materials embedded in the photonic crystal.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] John's idea was to use photonic crystals to affect localisation and control of light.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] After 1987, the number of research papers concerning photonic crystals began to grow exponentially.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] However, due to the difficulty of fabricating these structures at optical scales (see Fabrication challenges), early studies were either theoretical or in the microwave regime, where photonic crystals can be built on the more accessible centimetre scale.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] (This fact is due to a property of the electromagnetic fields known as scale invariance.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] By 1991, Yablonovitch had demonstrated the first three-dimensional photonic band-gap in the microwave regime.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] The structure that Yablonovitch was able to produce involved drilling an array of holes in a transparent material, where the holes of each layer form an inverse diamond structure – today it is known as Yablonovite.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] In 1996, Thomas Krauss demonstrated a two-dimensional photonic crystal at optical wavelengths.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] This opened the way to fabricate photonic crystals in semiconductor materials by borrowing methods from the semiconductor industry.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Pavel Cheben demonstrated a new type of photonic crystal waveguide – subwavelength grating (SWG) waveguide.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] The SWG waveguide operates in subwavelength region, away from the bandgap.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] It allows the waveguide properties to be controlled directly by the nanoscale engineering of the resulting metamaterial while mitigating wave interference effects.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] This provided "a missing degree of freedom in photonics" and resolved an important limitation in silicon photonics which was its restricted set of available materials insufficient to achieve complex optical on-chip functions.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Today, such techniques use photonic crystal slabs, which are two dimensional photonic crystals "etched" into slabs of semiconductor.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Total internal reflection confines light to the slab, and allows photonic crystal effects, such as engineering photonic dispersion in the slab.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Researchers around the world are looking for ways to use photonic crystal slabs in integrated computer chips, to improve optical processing of communications—both on-chip and between chips.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Titanium dioxide/silica and tantalum pentoxide/silica devices were produced, exploiting their dispersion characteristics and suitability to sputter deposition.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Such techniques have yet to mature into commercial applications, but two-dimensional photonic crystals are commercially used in photonic crystal fibres (otherwise known as holey fibres, because of the air holes that run through them).
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Photonic crystal fibres were first developed by Philip Russell in 1998, and can be designed to possess enhanced properties over (normal) optical fibres.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Study has proceeded more slowly in three-dimensional than in two-dimensional photonic crystals.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] This is because of more difficult fabrication.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Three-dimensional photonic crystal fabrication had no inheritable semiconductor industry techniques to draw on.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Attempts have been made, however, to adapt some of the same techniques, and quite advanced examples have been demonstrated, for example in the construction of "woodpile" structures constructed on a planar layer-by-layer basis.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Another strand of research has tried to construct three-dimensional photonic structures from self-assembly—essentially letting a mixture of dielectric nanospheres settle from solution into three-dimensionally periodic structures that have photonic band-gaps.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Vasily Astratov's group from the Ioffe Institute realized in 1995 that natural and synthetic opals are photonic crystals with an incomplete bandgap.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] The first demonstration of an "inverse opal" structure with a complete photonic bandgap came in 2000, from researchers at the University of Toronto, and Institute of Materials Science of Madrid (ICMM-CSIC), Spain.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] The ever-expanding field of natural photonics, bioinspiration and biomimetics—the study of natural structures to better understand and use them in design—is also helping researchers in photonic crystals.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] For example, in 2006 a naturally occurring photonic crystal was discovered in the scales of a Brazilian beetle.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Analogously, in 2012 a diamond crystal structure was found in a weevil and a gyroid-type architecture in a butterfly.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] More recently, gyroid photonic crystals have been found in the feather barbs of blue-winged leafbirds and are responsible for the bird's shimmery blue coloration.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Some publications suggest the feasibility of the complete photonic band gap in the visible range in photonic crystals with optically saturated media that can be implemented by using laser light as an external optical pump.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] The fabrication method depends on the number of dimensions that the photonic bandgap must exist in.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] To produce a one-dimensional photonic crystal, thin film layers of different dielectric constant may be periodically deposited on a surface which leads to a band gap in a particular propagation direction (such as normal to the surface).
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] A Bragg grating is an example of this type of photonic crystal.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] One-dimensional photonic crystals can include layers of non-linear optical materials in which the non-linear behaviour is accentuated due to field enhancement at wavelengths near a so-called degenerate band edge.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] This field enhancement (in terms of intensity) can reach $N^{2}$ where *N* is the total number of layers.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] However, by using layers which include an optically anisotropic material, it has been shown that the field enhancement can reach $N^{4}$ , which, in conjunction with non-linear optics, has potential applications such as in the development of an all-optical switch.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] A one-dimensional photonic crystal can be implemented using repeated alternating layers of a metamaterial and vacuum.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] If the metamaterial is such that the relative permittivity and permeability follow the same wavelength dependence, then the photonic crystal behaves identically for TE and TM modes, that is, for both *s* and *p* polarizations of light incident at an angle.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Recently, researchers fabricated a graphene-based Bragg grating (one-dimensional photonic crystal) and demonstrated that it supports excitation of surface electromagnetic waves in the periodic structure by using 633 nm He-Ne laser as the light source.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Besides, a novel type of one-dimensional graphene-dielectric photonic crystal has also been proposed.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] This structure can act as a far-IR filter and can support low-loss surface plasmons for waveguide and sensing applications.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] 1D photonic crystals doped with bio-active metals (i.e. silver) have been also proposed as sensing devices for bacterial contaminants.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Similar planar 1D photonic crystals made of polymers have been used to detect volatile organic compounds vapors in atmosphere.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] In addition to solid-phase photonic crystals, some liquid crystals with defined ordering can demonstrate photonic color.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] For example, studies have shown several liquid crystals with short- or long-range one-dimensional positional ordering can form photonic structures.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] In two dimensions, holes may be drilled in a substrate that is transparent to the wavelength of radiation that the bandgap is designed to block.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Triangular and square lattices of holes have been successfully employed.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] The **Holey fiber** or photonic crystal fiber can be made by taking cylindrical rods of glass in hexagonal lattice, and then heating and stretching them, the triangle-like airgaps between the glass rods become the holes that confine the modes.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Not only band gap, photonic crystals may have another effect if we partially remove the symmetry through the creation a nanosize cavity.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] This defect allows you to guide or to trap the light with the same function as nanophotonic resonator and it is characterized by the strong dielectric modulation in the photonic crystals.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] For the waveguide, the propagation of light depends on the in-plane control provided by the photonic band gap and to the long confinement of light induced by dielectric mismatch.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] For the light trap, the light is strongly confined in the cavity resulting further interactions with the materials.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] First, if we put a pulse of light inside the cavity, it will be delayed by nano- or picoseconds and this is proportional to the quality factor of the cavity.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Finally, if we put an emitter inside the cavity, the emission light also can be enhanced significantly and or even the resonant coupling can go through Rabi oscillation.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] This is related with cavity quantum electrodynamics and the interactions are defined by the weak and strong coupling of the emitter and the cavity.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] The first studies for the cavity in one-dimensional photonic slabs are usually in grating or distributed feedback structures.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] For two-dimensional photonic crystal cavities, they are useful to make efficient photonic devices in telecommunication applications as they can provide very high quality factor up to millions with smaller-than-wavelength mode volume.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] For three-dimensional photonic crystal cavities, several methods have been developed including lithographic layer-by-layer approach, surface ion beam lithography, and micromanipulation technique.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] All those mentioned photonic crystal cavities that tightly confine light offer very useful functionality for integrated photonic circuits, but it is challenging to produce them in a manner that allows them to be easily relocated.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] There is no full control with the cavity creation, the cavity location, and the emitter position relative to the maximum field of the cavity while the studies to solve those problems are still ongoing.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Movable cavity of nanowire in photonic crystals is one of solutions to tailor this light matter interaction.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] One promising fabrication method for two-dimensionally periodic photonic crystals is a photonic-crystal fiber, such as a *holey fiber*.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Using fiber draw techniques developed for communications fiber it meets these two requirements, and photonic crystal fibres are commercially available.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Another promising method for developing two-dimensional photonic crystals is the so-called photonic crystal slab.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] These structures consist of a slab of material—such as silicon—that can be patterned using techniques from the semiconductor industry.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Such chips offer the potential to combine photonic processing with electronic processing on a single chip.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] For three dimensional photonic crystals, various techniques have been used—including photolithography and etching techniques similar to those used for integrated circuits.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Some of these techniques are already commercially available.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] To avoid the complex machinery of nanotechnological methods, some alternate approaches involve growing photonic crystals from colloidal crystals as self-assembled structures.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Mass-scale 3D photonic crystal films and fibres can now be produced using a shear-assembly technique that stacks 200–300 nm colloidal polymer spheres into perfect films of fcc lattice.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Because the particles have a softer transparent rubber coating, the films can be stretched and molded, tuning the photonic bandgaps and producing striking structural color effects.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] The photonic band gap (PBG) is essentially the gap between the air-line and the dielectric-line in the dispersion relation of the PBG system.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Essentially, these methods solve for the frequencies (normal modes) of the photonic crystal for each value of the propagation direction given by the wave vector, or vice versa.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] The various lines in the band structure, correspond to the different cases of *n*, the band index.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] For an introduction to photonic band structure, see K.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Various open-source software for calculating band diagrams were also published in the photonics literature, including MPB.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] The **plane wave expansion** method can be used to calculate the band structure using an eigen formulation of the Maxwell's equations, and thus solving for the eigenfrequencies for each of the propagation directions, of the wave vectors.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] It directly solves for the dispersion diagram.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Electric field strength values can also be calculated over the spatial domain of the problem using the eigen vectors of the same problem.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] The **Inverse dispersion** method also exploited plane wave expansion but formulates Maxwell's equation as an eigenproblem for the wave vector k while the frequency $\omega$ is considered as a parameter.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Thus, it solves the dispersion relation $k(\omega )$ instead of $\omega (k)$ , which plane wave method does.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] The inverse dispersion method makes it possible to find complex value of the wave vector e.g. in the bandgap, which allows one to distinguish photonic crystals from metamaterial.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Besides, the method is ready for the frequency dispersion of the permittivity to be taken into account.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] To speed calculation of the frequency band structure, the **Reduced Bloch Mode Expansion (RBME)** method can be used.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] The RBME method applies "on top" of any of the primary expansion methods mentioned above.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] For large unit cell models, the RBME method can reduce time for computing the band structure by up to two orders of magnitude.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Photonic crystals are attractive optical materials for controlling and manipulating light flow.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] One dimensional photonic crystals are already in widespread use, in the form of thin-film optics, with applications from low and high reflection coatings on lenses and mirrors to colour changing paints and inks.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] Higher-dimensional photonic crystals are of great interest for both fundamental and applied research, and the two dimensional ones are beginning to find commercial applications.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] SWG nanophotonic couplers permit highly-efficient and polarization-independent coupling between photonic chips and external devices.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] They have been adopted for fibre-chip coupling in volume optoelectronic chip manufacturing.
[src:photonics/photonic-crystal] In addition to the foregoing, photonic crystals have been proposed as platforms for the development of solar cells and optical sensors, including chemical sensors and biosensors.
[src:photonics/photonics] Photonics is closely related to quantum optics, which studies the theory behind photonics' engineering applications.
[src:photonics/photonics] Though covering all light's technical applications over the whole spectrum, most photonic applications are in the range of visible and near-infrared light.
[src:photonics/photonics] The term *photonics* developed as an outgrowth of the first practical semiconductor light emitters invented in the early 1960s and optical fibers developed in the 1970s.
[src:photonics/photonics] The field is also supported by professional organizations such as the IEEE Photonics Society, which serves as a conduit for advances in photonics research, engineering, and its applications.
[src:photonics/photonics] An early instance of the word was in a December 1954 letter from John W.
[src:photonics/photonics] Photonics as a field began with the invention of the maser and laser in 1958 to 1960.
[src:photonics/photonics] Other developments followed: the laser diode in the 1970s, optical fibers for transmitting information, and the erbium-doped fiber amplifier.
[src:photonics/photonics] These inventions formed the basis for the telecommunications revolution of the late 20th century and provided the infrastructure for the Internet.
[src:photonics/photonics] Though coined earlier, the term photonics came into common use in the 1980s as fiber-optic data transmission was adopted by telecommunications network operators.
[src:photonics/photonics] At that time, the term was used widely at Bell Laboratories.
[src:photonics/photonics] Its use was confirmed when the IEEE Lasers and Electro-Optics Society established an archival journal named Photonics Technology Letters at the end of the 1980s.
[src:photonics/photonics] During the period leading up to the dot-com crash circa 2001, photonics was a field focused largely on optical telecommunications.
[src:photonics/photonics] However, photonics covers a huge range of science and technology applications, including laser manufacturing, biological and chemical sensing, medical diagnostics and therapy, display technology, and optical computing.
[src:photonics/photonics] Classical optics long preceded the discovery that light is quantized, when Albert Einstein famously explained the photoelectric effect in 1905.
[src:photonics/photonics] Optics tools include the refracting lens, the reflecting mirror, and various optical components and instruments developed throughout the 15th to 19th centuries.
[src:photonics/photonics] Key tenets of classical optics, such as Huygens Principle, developed in the 17th century, Maxwell's Equations and the wave equations, developed in the 19th century, do not depend on quantum properties of light.
[src:photonics/photonics] Photonics is related to quantum optics, optomechanics, electro-optics, optoelectronics and quantum electronics.
[src:photonics/photonics] However, each area has slightly different connotations by scientific and government communities and in the marketplace.
[src:photonics/photonics] Quantum optics often connotes fundamental research, whereas photonics is used to connote applied research and development.
[src:photonics/photonics] The term optoelectronics connotes devices or circuits that comprise both electrical and optical functions, i.e., a thin-film semiconductor device.
[src:photonics/photonics] The term electro-optics came into earlier use and specifically encompasses nonlinear electrical-optical interactions applied, e.g., as bulk crystal modulators such as the Pockels cell, but also includes advanced imaging sensors.
[src:photonics/photonics] An important aspect in the modern definition of Photonics is that there is not necessarily a widespread agreement in the perception of the field boundaries.
[src:photonics/photonics] In practice, as the field evolves, evidences that "modern optics" and Photonics are often used interchangeably are very diffused and absorbed in the scientific jargon.
[src:photonics/photonics] Photonics also relates to the emerging science of quantum information and quantum optics.
[src:photonics/photonics] Applications of photonics are ubiquitous.
[src:photonics/photonics] Just as applications of electronics have expanded dramatically since the first transistor was invented in 1948, the unique applications of photonics continue to emerge.
[src:photonics/photonics] Economically important applications for semiconductor photonic devices include optical data recording, fiber optic telecommunications, laser printing (based on xerography), displays, and optical pumping of high-power lasers.
[src:photonics/photonics] The potential applications of photonics are virtually unlimited and include chemical synthesis, medical diagnostics, on-chip data communication, sensors, laser defense, and fusion energy, to name several interesting additional examples.
[src:photonics/photonics] Microphotonics and nanophotonics usually includes photonic crystals and solid state devices.
[src:photonics/photonics] Photonics commonly uses semiconductor-based light sources, such as light-emitting diodes (LEDs), superluminescent diodes, and lasers.
[src:photonics/photonics] Other light sources include single photon sources, fluorescent lamps, cathode-ray tubes (CRTs), and plasma screens.
[src:photonics/photonics] Note that while CRTs, plasma screens, and organic light-emitting diode displays generate their own light, liquid crystal displays (LCDs) like TFT screens require a backlight of either cold cathode fluorescent lamps or, more often today, LEDs.
[src:photonics/photonics] Characteristic for research on semiconductor light sources is the frequent use of III-V semiconductors instead of the classical semiconductors like silicon and germanium.
[src:photonics/photonics] This is due to the special properties of III-V semiconductors that allow for the implementation of light emitting devices.
[src:photonics/photonics] Examples for material systems used are gallium arsenide (GaAs) and aluminium gallium arsenide (AlGaAs) or other compound semiconductors.
[src:photonics/photonics] They are also used in conjunction with silicon to produce hybrid silicon lasers.
[src:photonics/photonics] Light can be transmitted through any transparent medium.
[src:photonics/photonics] Glass fiber or plastic optical fiber can be used to guide the light along a desired path.
[src:photonics/photonics] In optical communications optical fibers allow for transmission distances of more than 100 km without amplification depending on the bit rate and modulation format used for transmission.
[src:photonics/photonics] A very advanced research topic within photonics is the investigation and fabrication of special structures and "materials" with engineered optical properties.
[src:photonics/photonics] These include photonic crystals, photonic crystal fibers and metamaterials.
[src:photonics/photonics] Optical amplifiers are used to amplify an optical signal.
[src:photonics/photonics] Optical amplifiers used in optical communications are erbium-doped fiber amplifiers, semiconductor optical amplifiers, Raman amplifiers and optical parametric amplifiers.
[src:photonics/photonics] A very advanced research topic on optical amplifiers is the research on quantum dot semiconductor optical amplifiers.
[src:photonics/photonics] Photodetectors range from very fast photodiodes for communications applications over medium speed charge coupled devices (CCDs) for digital cameras to very slow solar cells that are used for energy harvesting from sunlight.
[src:photonics/photonics] There are also many other photodetectors based on thermal, chemical, quantum, photoelectric and other effects.
[src:photonics/photonics] Modulation of a light source is used to encode information on a light source.
[src:photonics/photonics] Modulation can be achieved by the light source directly.
[src:photonics/photonics] One of the simplest examples is to use a flashlight to send Morse code.
[src:photonics/photonics] Another method is to take the light from a light source and modulate it in an external optical modulator.
[src:photonics/photonics] An additional topic covered by modulation research is the modulation format.
[src:photonics/photonics] On-off keying has been the commonly used modulation format in optical communications.
[src:photonics/photonics] In the last years more advanced modulation formats like phase-shift keying or even orthogonal frequency-division multiplexing have been investigated to counteract effects like dispersion that degrade the quality of the transmitted signal.
[src:photonics/photonics] Photonics also includes research on photonic systems.
[src:photonics/photonics] This term is often used for optical communication systems.
[src:photonics/photonics] This area of research focuses on the implementation of photonic systems like high speed photonic networks.
[src:photonics/photonics] This also includes research on Optical communications repeaters, which improve optical signal quality.
[src:photonics/photonics] Photonic integrated circuits (PICs) are optically active integrated semiconductor photonic devices.
[src:photonics/photonics] The leading commercial application of PICs are optical transceivers for data center optical networks.
[src:photonics/photonics] PICs fabricated on III-V indium phosphide semiconductor wafer substrates were the first to achieve commercial success; PICs based on silicon wafer substrates are now also a commercialized technology.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] An **optical waveguide** is a physical structure that guides electromagnetic waves in the optical spectrum.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] Common types of optical waveguides include optical fiber waveguides, transparent dielectric waveguides made of plastic and glass, liquid light guides, and liquid waveguides.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] Optical waveguides are used as components in integrated optical circuits or as the transmission medium in local and long-haul optical communication systems.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] They can also be used in optical head-mounted displays in augmented reality.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] Optical waveguides can be classified according to their geometry (planar, strip, or fiber waveguides), mode structure (single-mode, multi-mode), refractive index distribution (step or gradient index), and material (glass, polymer, semiconductor).
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] The basic principles behind optical waveguides can be described using the concepts of geometrical or ray optics, as illustrated in the diagram.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] Light passing into a medium with higher refractive index bends toward the normal by the process of refraction (Figure **a.**).
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] Take, for example, light passing from air into glass.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] Similarly, light traveling in the opposite direction (from glass into air) takes the same path, bending away from the normal.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] This is a consequence of time-reversal symmetry.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] Each ray in air (black) can be mapped to a ray in the glass (blue), as shown in Figure **b**.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] But because of refraction, some of the rays in the glass are left out (red).
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] The remaining rays are trapped in the glass by a process called *total internal reflection*.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] They are incident on the glass-air interface at an angle above the *critical angle*.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] These extra rays correspond to a higher *density of states* in more-advanced formulations based on the Green's function.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] Using total internal reflection, light can be trapped and guided in a dielectric waveguide (Figure **c**).
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] The red rays bounce off both the top and bottom surface of the high index medium.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] They're guided even if the slab curves or bends, so long as it bends slowly.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] This is the basic principle behind fiber optics in which light is guided along a high index glass *core* in a lower index glass *cladding* (Figure **d**).
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] Ray optics only gives a rough picture of how waveguides work.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] Maxwell's equations can be solved by analytical or numerical methods for a full-field description of a dielectric waveguide.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] Perhaps the simplest optical waveguide is the dielectric **slab waveguide**, also called a **planar waveguide**.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] Owing to their simplicity, slab waveguides are often used as toy models but also find application in on-chip devices like arrayed waveguide gratings and acousto-optic filters and modulators.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] The slab waveguide consists of three layers of materials with different dielectric constants, extending infinitely in the directions parallel to their interfaces.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] Light is confined in the middle layer by total internal reflection if the refractive index of the middle layer is larger than that of the surrounding layers.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] The slab waveguide is essentially a one-dimensional waveguide.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] It traps light only normal to the dielectric interfaces.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] For guided modes, the field in domain II in the diagram is propagating and can be treated as a plane wave.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] The field in domains I and III evanescently decay away from the slab.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] The plane wave in domain II bounces between the top and bottom interfaces at some angle typically specified by the ${\vec {\beta }}$ , the wave vector in the plane of the slab.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] Guided modes constructively interfere on one complete roundtrip in the slab.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] At each frequency, one or more modes can be found giving a set of eigenvalues $(\omega ,{\vec {\beta }})$ which can be used to construct a band diagram or dispersion relation.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] Because guided modes are trapped in the slab, they cannot be excited by light incident on the top or bottom interfaces.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] Light can be *end-fire or butte coupled* by injecting it with a lens in the plane of the slab.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] Alternatively a coupling element may be used to couple light into the waveguide, such as a grating coupler or prism coupler.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] There are two technologies: diffractive waveguides and reflective waveguides.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] A **strip waveguide** is basically a strip of the layer confined between cladding layers.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] The simplest case is a **rectangular waveguide**, which is formed when the guiding layer of the slab waveguide is restricted in both transverse directions rather than just one.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] Rectangular waveguides are used in integrated optical circuits and in laser diodes.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] They are commonly used as the basis of such optical components as Mach–Zehnder interferometers and wavelength division multiplexers.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] The cavities of laser diodes are frequently constructed as rectangular optical waveguides.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] Optical waveguides with rectangular geometry are produced by a variety of means, usually by a planar process.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] The field distribution in a rectangular waveguide cannot be solved analytically, however approximate solution methods, such as Marcatili's method, Extended Marcatili's method and Kumar's method, are known.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] A **rib waveguide** is a waveguide in which the guiding layer basically consists of the slab with a strip (or several strips) superimposed onto it.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] Rib waveguides also provide confinement of the wave in two dimensions and near-unity confinement is possible in multi-layer rib structures.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] Optical waveguides typically maintain a constant cross-section along their direction of propagation.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] This is for example the case for strip and of rib waveguides.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] However, waveguides can also have periodic changes in their cross-section while still allowing lossless transmission of light via so-called Bloch modes.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] Such waveguides are referred to as segmented waveguides (with a 1D patterning along the direction of propagation) or as photonic crystal waveguides (with a 2D or 3D patterning).
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] Optical waveguides find their most important application in photonics.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] Configuring the waveguides in 3D space provides integration between electronic components on a chip and optical fibers.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] Such waveguides may be designed for a single mode propagation of infrared light at telecommunication wavelengths, and configured to deliver optical signal between input and output locations with very low loss.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] One of the methods for constructing such waveguides utilizes photorefractive effect in transparent materials.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] An increase in the refractive index of a material may be induced by nonlinear absorption of pulsed laser light.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] In order to maximize the increase of the refractive index, a very short (typically femtosecond) laser pulses are used, and focused with a high NA microscope objective.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] By translating the focal spot through a bulk transparent material the waveguides can be directly written.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] A variation of this method uses a low NA microscope objective and translates the focal spot along the beam axis.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] This improves the overlap between the focused laser beam and the photorefractive material, thus reducing power needed from the laser.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] When transparent material is exposed to an unfocused laser beam of sufficient brightness to initiate photorefractive effect, the waveguides may start forming on their own as a result of an accumulated self-focusing.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] The formation of such waveguides leads to a breakup of the laser beam.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] Continued exposure results in a buildup of the refractive index towards the centerline of each waveguide, and collapse of the mode field diameter of the propagating light.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] Such waveguides remain permanently in the glass and can be photographed off-line (see the picture on the right).
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] Light pipes are tubes or cylinders of solid material used to guide light a short distance.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] In electronics, plastic light pipes are used to guide light from LEDs on a circuit board to the user interface surface.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] In buildings, light pipes are used to transfer illumination from outside the building to where it is needed inside.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] Optical fiber is typically a circular cross-section *dielectric waveguide* consisting of a dielectric material surrounded by another dielectric material with a lower refractive index.
[src:photonics/waveguide-optics] Optical fibers are most commonly made from silica glass, however other glass materials are used for certain applications and plastic optical fiber can be used for short-distance applications.
